00:46:37,671 --> 00:46:39,880
DARDIS:
Well, I doubt it started off as pesos.

699
00:46:40,048 --> 00:46:41,590
CARL:
Uh...

700
00:46:41,758 --> 00:46:44,969
- Well, wait a minute, what's this one?
DARDIS: Uh, what's...? Okay, $25,000.

701
00:46:45,136 --> 00:46:47,888
CARL: Who's that? Who is that? Dahl...?
DARDIS: Kenneth H. Dahlberg.

702
00:46:48,056 --> 00:46:50,057
We haven't been able to ascertain
who that is.

703
00:46:50,308 --> 00:46:52,559
Bob, I've got something.
I don't know what it is.

704
00:46:52,727 --> 00:46:54,728
Somewhere,
there is a Kenneth H. Dahlberg.

705
00:46:54,896 --> 00:46:57,272
We gotta get to him
before the New York Times does.

706
00:46:57,440 --> 00:47:00,693
I think they have the same information.
Got a pencil? Write this down.

707
00:47:00,860 --> 00:47:04,780
Kenneth H. Dahlberg.
D-A-H-L-B-E-R-G, Dahlberg.

708
00:47:05,907 --> 00:47:09,159
MAN [ON RADIO]: McGovern, who at first
voiced complete support for Eagleton...

709
00:47:09,327 --> 00:47:12,997
...has more recently expressed doubts
and said Eagleton must make a decision...

710
00:47:13,164 --> 00:47:15,249
...whether to stay or leave the ticket.

711
00:47:15,417 --> 00:47:16,959
More with Jean Westwood...

712
00:47:17,127 --> 00:47:20,045
WOMAN: You're the one that wanted
the articles on Kenneth H. Dahlberg?

713
00:47:20,213 --> 00:47:22,756
- Yeah. - Couldn't find anything
in the clip file at all.

714
00:47:22,924 --> 00:47:24,633
- Oh, wonderful.
- Um...

715
00:47:24,926 --> 00:47:28,637
I did find one picture though,
if it's any help.

716
00:47:30,515 --> 00:47:32,016
- Thanks.
- Mm.

717
00:47:32,600 --> 00:47:34,601
[MAN 1 SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON RADIO]

718
00:47:37,397 --> 00:47:39,064
BOB:
Minnesota.

719
00:47:39,232 --> 00:47:41,233
MAN 1 [ON RADIO]:
...supported Senator Eagleman.

720
00:47:41,401 --> 00:47:44,778
He is an able United States senator...

721
00:47:44,946 --> 00:47:46,113
BOB:
Minneapolis, Minneapolis.

722
00:47:46,281 --> 00:47:50,325
...will make him a prominent figure
in American politics...

723
00:47:50,493 --> 00:47:52,786
...for many, many years.

724
00:47:53,455 --> 00:47:55,456
[CROWD APPLAUDING ON RADIO]

725
00:48:02,297 --> 00:48:07,885
I base that conclusion
upon my conversations with his doctors...

726
00:48:08,053 --> 00:48:11,513
...and my close personal
and political association with him.

727
00:48:11,681 --> 00:48:13,807
- Outside line, please.
WOMAN 1 [OVER PHONE]: Yes.

728
00:48:13,975 --> 00:48:15,684
- Thank you.
MAN 1 [ON RADIO]: In the joint decision...

729
00:48:15,852 --> 00:48:20,314
...that we have reached tonight,
health was not a factor.

730
00:48:20,482 --> 00:48:26,111
But the public debate over
Senator Eagleman's past medical history...

731
00:48:26,279 --> 00:48:30,532
...continues to divert attention
from the great national issues...

732
00:48:30,700 --> 00:48:33,077
...that need to be discussed.

733
00:48:33,244 --> 00:48:39,666
I have referred to the growing pressures
to ask for Senator Eagleton's withdrawal.

734
00:48:39,834 --> 00:48:42,628
- We have also seen...
DAHLBERG [OVER PHONE]: Hello?

735
00:48:42,796 --> 00:48:44,630
- Could I please...? Mr. Dahlberg?
- Yes?

736
00:48:44,798 --> 00:48:47,382
- Kenneth Dahlberg?
- Yes?

737
00:48:47,550 --> 00:48:50,844
This is Bob Woodward
of the Washington Post.

738
00:48:51,679 --> 00:48:53,847
- Yes?
- About that $25,000 check...

739
00:48:54,015 --> 00:48:57,184
...deposited in the bank account
of one of the Watergate burglars...

740
00:48:57,352 --> 00:48:59,269
...Mr. Bernard Barker.

741
00:49:01,523 --> 00:49:04,650
As you know, sir,
the check has your name on it.

742
00:49:05,360 --> 00:49:06,819
We were doing a story on this...

743
00:49:06,986 --> 00:49:09,988
...and I was wondering if you would care
to comment or explain.

744
00:49:10,156 --> 00:49:13,700
Uh, I turn all my money over
to the committee.

745
00:49:13,868 --> 00:49:16,453
What committee is that, sir?
The Committee to Reelect?

746
00:49:16,621 --> 00:49:19,665
- Yes, yes.
- And why would you do that?

747
00:49:19,833 --> 00:49:22,000
MAN 2: That's it, he's done.
- I raise a lot of money.

748
00:49:22,168 --> 00:49:25,420
I'm Midwest Finance chairman.

749
00:49:25,588 --> 00:49:27,881
For the Committee to Reelect?

750
00:49:28,508 --> 00:49:31,009
- Hello?
- Yes, that's right.

751
00:49:31,177 --> 00:49:35,055
How do you think your check got into
the bank account of the Watergate burglar?

752
00:49:35,223 --> 00:49:40,227
I'm a proper citizen. What I do is proper.

753
00:49:40,395 --> 00:49:44,481
- Oh, I understand.
- I've just been through a terrible ordeal.

754
00:49:44,649 --> 00:49:47,693
- My neighbor's wife has been kidnapped.
- Oh.

755
00:49:47,861 --> 00:49:50,320
Well, how do you think your check
got into Barker's account, though...?

756
00:49:50,488 --> 00:49:51,530
[LINE DISCONNECTS]

757
00:49:51,698 --> 00:49:53,699
[SIGHS]

758
00:50:25,106 --> 00:50:26,815
WOMAN 2:
Committee to Reelect the President.

759
00:50:26,983 --> 00:50:28,400
Could I speak to Clark MacGregor?

760
00:50:28,568 --> 00:50:31,028
- One moment, I'll connect you.
- Thank you. Thank you.

761
00:50:32,780 --> 00:50:33,947
MacGREGOR: Yes?
- Mr. MacGregor?

762
00:50:34,115 --> 00:50:37,618
- Yes.
- Bob Woodward of the Washington Post.

763
00:50:38,244 --> 00:50:39,286
- Hello?
- Yes?

764
00:50:39,454 --> 00:50:41,580
Uh, this is Bob Woodward
of the Washington Post.

765
00:50:41,748 --> 00:50:42,789
Mm-hm.

766
00:50:42,957 --> 00:50:46,376
I just spoke to a Kenneth Dahlberg,
who says he is Midwest Finance chairman.

767
00:50:46,544 --> 00:50:48,670
Yeah, I know Ken Dahlberg.

768
00:50:48,838 --> 00:50:50,839
Well, I can't seem to get an explanation...

769
00:50:51,007 --> 00:50:53,842
...on why a check for $25,000
made out to Mr. Dahlberg...

770
00:50:54,010 --> 00:50:56,136
...that he sent
to the Committee to Reelect...

771
00:50:56,304 --> 00:50:58,805
...would end up in the account
of a Watergate burglar.

772
00:50:58,973 --> 00:51:00,265
I don't know.

773
00:51:00,433 --> 00:51:02,976
- But you're head of the committee.
- I just came aboard.

774
00:51:03,144 --> 00:51:05,646
John Mitchell was head of the committee.
He might know.

775
00:51:05,813 --> 00:51:08,315
- What would the explanation possibly...?
- I don't know.

776
00:51:08,483 --> 00:51:10,150
You're implying that I should know.

777
00:51:10,318 --> 00:51:13,695
If you print that,
our relationship will be terminated.

778
00:51:14,781 --> 00:51:16,114
We don't have a relationship.

779
00:51:16,282 --> 00:51:19,117
The issues of the campaign
are peace and prosperity...

780
00:51:19,285 --> 00:51:21,286
...not a campaign check.

781
00:51:21,454 --> 00:51:22,788
WOMAN 3: Bob.
- Sir, no one is saying...

782
00:51:22,956 --> 00:51:24,831
WOMAN 3: Bob.
- This happened before I came aboard.

783
00:51:24,999 --> 00:51:28,168
WOMAN 3: Mr. Dahlberg is on Line 2.
- I'm running a campaign.

784
00:51:28,336 --> 00:51:32,381
We've raised $60 million,
and you're asking about a $25,000 check.

785
00:51:32,548 --> 00:51:35,342
Mr. MacGregor, excuse me,
could you hold one second, please?

786
00:51:35,510 --> 00:51:36,843
- All right.
- Thank you. Yes?

787
00:51:37,011 --> 00:51:38,595
DAHLBERG: Hello?
- Mr. Dahlberg?

788
00:51:38,763 --> 00:51:40,847
- Yes.
- Could you please hold one second, sir?

789
00:51:41,015 --> 00:51:42,516
- Yes.
- Thank you. Mr. MacGregor?

790
00:51:42,684 --> 00:51:44,226
MacGREGOR: Yeah?
- Can I call you right back?

791
00:51:44,394 --> 00:51:46,687
- Yeah, okay.
- Thank you. Mr. Dahlberg.

792
00:51:46,854 --> 00:51:50,065
DAHLBERG:
Yes. Uh, I'm sorry I hung up before.

793
00:51:50,233 --> 00:51:53,110
I wasn't sure you were
a Washington Post reporter.

794
00:51:53,278 --> 00:51:56,780
I believe we were talking
about a $25,000 check.

795
00:51:56,948 --> 00:52:00,951
Um... Obviously, this is difficult for me.

796
00:52:01,119 --> 00:52:04,538
Uh, I'm caught
in the middle of something...

797
00:52:04,706 --> 00:52:06,540
...and I don't know what.

798
00:52:06,708 --> 00:52:09,501
- I don't...
- What do you think it could be?

799
00:52:09,669 --> 00:52:11,692
Well, I deal with a lot
of important people.

800
00:52:11,693 --> 00:52:13,714
People who work
for the committee?

801
00:52:13,881 --> 00:52:15,382
- Hello?
- For the committee.

802
00:52:15,550 --> 00:52:18,260
- The Committee to Reelect the President?
- Yes.

803
00:52:18,428 --> 00:52:20,762
You see, I raised that money in cash...

804
00:52:20,930 --> 00:52:23,557
...and I have a winter home in Florida.

805
00:52:23,725 --> 00:52:26,727
- Is that in Miami?
- Boca Raton.

806
00:52:26,894 --> 00:52:29,730
And I didn't want to carry
all that cash around.

807
00:52:29,897 --> 00:52:32,399
- Now, you can understand that.
- Oh, of course I can.

808
00:52:32,567 --> 00:52:35,235
So I had it exchanged
for the cashier's check.

809
00:52:35,403 --> 00:52:38,655
And how do you think
it got into Barker's account?

810
00:52:38,823 --> 00:52:40,240
Uh...

811
00:52:40,575 --> 00:52:44,244
I know I shouldn't be telling you this.
Uh...

812
00:52:45,955 --> 00:52:49,499
I gave it to Mr. Stans.

813
00:52:52,086 --> 00:52:53,837
I beg your pardon?

814
00:52:54,005 --> 00:52:57,591
- I gave it to Stans.
- Maurice Stans?

815
00:52:57,759 --> 00:53:01,053
- The head of Finance for Nixon?
- Yes, in Washington.

816
00:53:01,220 --> 00:53:05,390
Now, what he did with it,
I really do not know.

817
00:53:05,558 --> 00:53:09,227
I see. Were there any other checks that
you might be aware of, that could've...?

818
00:53:09,395 --> 00:53:12,314
That's all I have to say.

819
00:53:12,482 --> 00:53:18,111
Mr. MacGregor... Mr. Dahlberg, I'm sorry.
Thank you very much.

820
00:53:28,956 --> 00:53:30,957
[TYPEWRITER CLACKING]

821
00:53:32,085 --> 00:53:35,128
WOMAN 3:
Metro Desk. Yeah, he's here, hold on.

822
00:53:35,296 --> 00:53:36,296
- Bob.
- Yeah?

823
00:53:36,464 --> 00:53:38,465
Carl Bernstein on Line 1.

824
00:53:38,633 --> 00:53:40,217
- One?
- Yeah.

825
00:53:40,385 --> 00:53:43,095
BOB: Yeah?
CARL: Woodward? I got a lead on Dahlberg.

826
00:53:43,262 --> 00:53:44,971
- I just... I got it.
- What?

827
00:53:45,139 --> 00:53:48,266
I just talked to him. I just hung up.
It goes all the way to Stans.

828
00:53:48,434 --> 00:53:50,143
- What?
- It goes all the way to Stans.

829
00:53:50,311 --> 00:53:52,854
He gave the check to Stans
for the Committee to Reelect.

830
00:53:53,022 --> 00:53:55,816
- Did he say that?
- He said it. I've got it in my notes.

831
00:53:55,983 --> 00:53:57,818
- Jesus.
- It's down on record, Bernstein.

832
00:53:57,985 --> 00:54:00,195
That money winds up
in the account of a burglar?

833
00:54:00,363 --> 00:54:02,697
- Yes. Ha-ha-ha.
- Fantastic. I'm coming home.

834
00:54:02,865 --> 00:54:04,324
Okay.

835
00:54:05,410 --> 00:54:08,745
MAN:... catapulted the unknown senator
from Missouri into national prominence...

836
00:54:08,913 --> 00:54:13,792
...by naming Eagleton as his running mate.
The move surprised the old pros...

837
00:54:13,960 --> 00:54:17,421
...but it paid off in support
for the Democratic ticket.

838
00:54:17,672 --> 00:54:20,549
HOWARD: What happened with that
Taiwan thing you were telling us about?

839
00:54:20,716 --> 00:54:24,678
Japan is going to break diplomatic ties
with Taiwan and recognize they're China.

840
00:54:24,846 --> 00:54:28,181
The irony, of course, that's a direct
result of Nixon's visit to China.

841
00:54:28,349 --> 00:54:30,016
What did he say to him?

842
00:54:30,184 --> 00:54:32,060
DUNLAP:
That's a great parallel story...

843
00:54:32,228 --> 00:54:34,688
...if you're going to
do that piece on dtente.

844
00:54:34,897 --> 00:54:39,276
Uh... "Queen Elizabeth proclaims a state
of emergency to deal with the dock strike."

845
00:54:39,444 --> 00:54:40,902
BEN:
Bringing it off his boat.

846
00:54:41,070 --> 00:54:42,946
[ALL LAUGHING]

847
00:54:43,114 --> 00:54:44,531
DUNLAP:
That could be a human-interest.

848
00:54:44,699 --> 00:54:46,741
Thirty-one days of rain
in the Philippines...

849
00:54:46,909 --> 00:54:49,202
...being blamed on the theft
of a statue of Jesus.

850
00:54:49,370 --> 00:54:51,830
- We had one like that before.
- Front-page article.

851
00:54:51,998 --> 00:54:54,291
- Absolutely not.
MAN 1: I'll put my best writer on that.

852
00:54:54,459 --> 00:54:55,709
MAN 2: What about
the one in India months ago?

853
00:54:55,877 --> 00:54:56,877
Drop that.

854
00:54:57,044 --> 00:54:59,713
Laugh, gentlemen.
It'll be the only story everyone reads.

855
00:54:59,881 --> 00:55:01,548
Okay. National?

856
00:55:01,716 --> 00:55:04,176
We have the Bremer diary,
wished to kill Nixon.

857
00:55:04,343 --> 00:55:07,429
He took a car trip to New York,
Ottawa and Washington to kill him.

858
00:55:07,597 --> 00:55:08,722
HOWARD: Jesus Christ.
HARRY: Yeah.

859
00:55:08,890 --> 00:55:11,683
We have the Senate
approving the ABM Treaty.

860
00:55:11,851 --> 00:55:13,059
- Yeah, that's mine.
HOWARD: ABM.

861
00:55:13,227 --> 00:55:17,981
And, of course, we have McGovern
offering the VP spot to everybody.

862
00:55:18,149 --> 00:55:19,441
- Yeah, that's news.
- I have...

863
00:55:19,609 --> 00:55:22,360
Everybody's been offered it.
I'll tell you what'll be news.

864
00:55:22,528 --> 00:55:24,237
When somebody accepts it.
That'll be news.

865
00:55:24,405 --> 00:55:25,447
[ALL CHUCKLING]

866
00:55:25,615 --> 00:55:26,865
MAN 3: Yeah.
- Here is some great art.

867
00:55:27,033 --> 00:55:28,074
HOWARD:
Yeah, big mistake.

868
00:55:28,242 --> 00:55:31,912
McGovern and Humphrey, breakfast,
smiling their asses off.

869
00:55:32,079 --> 00:55:34,080
- Isn't that great?
- Oh, look at that.

870
00:55:34,248 --> 00:55:36,416
MOFFITT:
Humphrey said, "I am George's friend."

871
00:55:36,584 --> 00:55:38,126
Why is that man smiling?

872
00:55:38,294 --> 00:55:40,212
MOFFITT: "I am his friend."
- Sounds friendly, huh?

873
00:55:40,379 --> 00:55:42,923
MOFFITT: "I'll be helping him in ways
he never dreamed possible."

874
00:55:43,090 --> 00:55:45,884
MAN 4:
Breakfast followed by lunch.

875
00:55:46,052 --> 00:55:48,428
MOFFITT: Got a good picture?
- Okay. Metro?

876
00:55:48,596 --> 00:55:50,931
Well, we got the schoolteachers
on Capitol Hill.

877
00:55:51,098 --> 00:55:55,310
They want a 17% increase in pay,
or this fall they go on strike.

878
00:55:55,478 --> 00:55:58,563
Harry, I think we could mention
that this might be the time...

879
00:55:58,731 --> 00:56:01,525
...to go to the front page
on the District Home Rule.

880
00:56:01,692 --> 00:56:02,984
BEN: Oh, come on.
- Listen to him.

881
00:56:03,152 --> 00:56:06,446
Ben, this time it could go all the way.

882
00:56:06,614 --> 00:56:09,366
The House is gonna vote next week
on a Senate resolution.

883
00:56:09,534 --> 00:56:11,409
When they pass it, we'll run with it.

884
00:56:11,577 --> 00:56:14,120
Okay, fellas, let's go around again now.
Foreign?

885
00:56:14,288 --> 00:56:17,707
- Uh, Taiwan emergency, Philippines.
- Okay, fine. National?

886
00:56:17,875 --> 00:56:21,127
The Eagleton follow-ups, McGovern
not being able to get a replacement.

887
00:56:21,295 --> 00:56:23,547
He's offered it to Humphrey,
Kennedy and Ribicoff.

888
00:56:23,714 --> 00:56:25,715
All turned him down.
That's the Page 1 lead.

889
00:56:25,883 --> 00:56:28,677
You're ignoring the importance
of the Dahlberg repercussions.

890
00:56:28,844 --> 00:56:30,971
Nobody cares
about the Dahlberg repercussions.

891
00:56:31,138 --> 00:56:35,642
Our story got the General Accounting Office
to start an audit with CREEP Finance.

892
00:56:35,810 --> 00:56:39,437
Yeah, we printed that, didn't we? When
the audit's done, we'll print that too.

893
00:56:39,605 --> 00:56:41,314
MOFFITT:
Let me tell you what happened today.

894
00:56:41,482 --> 00:56:43,400
I was having lunch
at the Sans Souci and...

895
00:56:43,568 --> 00:56:46,528
ALL: Aww...
HOWARD: How much this time?

896
00:56:46,696 --> 00:56:49,447
This White House guy, a good one, a pro,
came up and asked:

897
00:56:49,615 --> 00:56:51,866
"What is this Watergate compulsion
with you guys?"

898
00:56:52,034 --> 00:56:53,076
Compulsion?

899
00:56:53,244 --> 00:56:55,579
- I said...
- This is a story. This is not compulsion.

900
00:56:55,746 --> 00:56:58,164
I said, "Well, we think it's important,"
and he said:

901
00:56:58,332 --> 00:56:59,874
"If it's so goddamn important...

902
00:57:00,042 --> 00:57:02,168
...who in the hell are Woodward
and Bernstein?"

903
00:57:02,336 --> 00:57:05,714
What do you expect from the White House?
"You're doing a great job"?

904
00:57:05,881 --> 00:57:08,216
Now, why don't you ask him
what he's really saying?

905
00:57:08,384 --> 00:57:10,677
He wants to take the story away
from Woodstein...

906
00:57:10,845 --> 00:57:12,304
...and give it to National Desk.

907
00:57:12,471 --> 00:57:14,347
I have experienced guys sitting around...

908
00:57:14,515 --> 00:57:16,683
...who know the politicians,
have the contacts.

909
00:57:16,851 --> 00:57:19,185
HOWARD: We're aware of that.
- You said it. Sitting around.

910
00:57:19,353 --> 00:57:23,315
Ben. It's a dangerous story for this paper.

911
00:57:24,066 --> 00:57:27,444
MOFFITT: What if your boys get it wrong?
- Then it's our ass, isn't it?

912
00:57:27,612 --> 00:57:30,363
HOWARD: We all have to go
out and work for a living.

913
00:57:30,823 --> 00:57:34,701
National gets eight columns.
Nine for Foreign.

914
00:57:34,869 --> 00:57:37,537
Metro, 15.

915
00:57:37,705 --> 00:57:40,081
- That's it, fellas.
- Okay.

916
00:57:40,249 --> 00:57:42,042
Could've been worse.

917
00:57:43,544 --> 00:57:46,379
BEN:
Hey, Scott, I need to see you.

918
00:57:48,007 --> 00:57:49,049
How dangerous?

919
00:57:49,216 --> 00:57:51,384
[DOOR CLOSES]

920
00:57:51,552 --> 00:57:53,553
[SIGHS]

921
00:57:54,180 --> 00:57:57,891
Well, it's not just that we're using
unnamed sources that bothers me...

922
00:57:58,059 --> 00:58:00,727
...or that everything we print,
the White House denies...

923
00:58:02,146 --> 00:58:05,440
...or that almost no other papers
are reprinting our stuff.

924
00:58:05,608 --> 00:58:07,067
What, then?

925
00:58:07,234 --> 00:58:09,569
Look, there are over 2000 reporters
in this town...

926
00:58:09,737 --> 00:58:12,447
...and there are five on Watergate?

927
00:58:12,615 --> 00:58:16,493
Where did the Washington Post
suddenly get the monopoly on wisdom?

928
00:58:17,453 --> 00:58:19,204
Why would the Republicans do it?

929
00:58:20,122 --> 00:58:21,581
McGovern is self-destructing...

930
00:58:21,749 --> 00:58:24,584
...just like Humphrey, Muskie,
the bunch of them.

931
00:58:26,587 --> 00:58:28,838
I don't believe the story.

932
00:58:29,548 --> 00:58:31,758
Doesn't make sense.

933
00:58:33,719 --> 00:58:35,595
Yeah, Bernstein.

934
00:58:35,763 --> 00:58:37,597
Now? All right.

935
00:58:37,765 --> 00:58:41,017
Woodward, Bradlee will see us now.
Answer the phone for me.

936
00:58:41,185 --> 00:58:44,437
MAN 1: Are you trying to find
the lowest possible common denominator?

937
00:58:44,605 --> 00:58:47,232
Is that your plan in the convention?

938
00:58:47,400 --> 00:58:49,275
MAN 2:
Gonna give us something to do?

939
00:58:49,443 --> 00:58:53,488
WOMAN 1: Bob, Frances is on the phone.
BOB: Tell her I'll call her back.

940
00:58:54,865 --> 00:58:56,908
MAN 3:
All right, in this...

941
00:58:59,120 --> 00:59:03,957
WOMAN 2: We have reports that Republican
Les Aspin has informed the secretary of...

942
00:59:04,125 --> 00:59:05,417
MICKEY:
Ben, it's the hottest item.

943
00:59:05,584 --> 00:59:07,293
- It's in over 500 papers.
- What is it?

944
00:59:07,461 --> 00:59:10,797
MICKEY: Yesterday's weather report for
people who were drunk and slept all day.

945
00:59:10,965 --> 00:59:13,466
Send it to the San Francisco Chronicle.
They need it.

946
00:59:13,634 --> 00:59:15,301
MICKEY: How about the crossword puzzle?
- No.

947
00:59:15,469 --> 00:59:18,805
MICKEY: Anagrams?
- No space. No space, Mickey.

948
00:59:18,973 --> 00:59:21,891
MICKEY: You guys, last thing you
bought from me was the obituaries.

949
00:59:22,059 --> 00:59:25,520
- Make them buy something, will you?
BEN: All right. Hey, what do you guys want?

950
00:59:25,688 --> 00:59:28,648
The GAO reports are due out
the morning of Nixon's renomination.

951
00:59:28,816 --> 00:59:30,483
Hey, sit down, sit down.

952
00:59:30,651 --> 00:59:33,153
Well, that's two weeks from now.

953
00:59:33,487 --> 00:59:35,572
Since they're only responsible
to Congress...

954
00:59:35,740 --> 00:59:38,324
...no way the White House
can control the investigation.

955
00:59:38,492 --> 00:59:40,452
A source at General Accounting tells us...

956
00:59:40,619 --> 00:59:44,164
...there's a whole rat's nest
of illegal shit going on over at CREEP.

957
00:59:44,331 --> 00:59:46,040
- Like what?
- Like a slush fund.

958
00:59:46,208 --> 00:59:48,835
Hundreds of thousands of dollars
of unaccounted-for cash.

959
00:59:49,003 --> 00:59:50,545
BEN:
Hundreds of thousands of dollars?

960
00:59:50,713 --> 00:59:53,298
HOWARD: Any comment from CREEP?
- Yes, unavailable for comment.

961
00:59:53,466 --> 00:59:54,507
They're not talking.

962
00:59:54,675 --> 00:59:58,094
What else besides the money?
Where's the goddamn story?

963
00:59:59,847 --> 01:00:02,432
- The money's the key to whatever this is.
- Says who?

964
01:00:02,600 --> 01:00:03,683
HOWARD: Deep Throat.
- Who?

965
01:00:03,851 --> 01:00:07,270
Oh, that's Woodward's garage freak,
his source in the executive.

966
01:00:07,438 --> 01:00:08,480
Garage freak?

967
01:00:08,647 --> 01:00:11,608
Jesus, what kind
of a crazy fucking story is this?

968
01:00:11,776 --> 01:00:12,817
Who did you say?

969
01:00:13,694 --> 01:00:15,487
[SIGHS]

970
01:00:15,654 --> 01:00:19,866
He's on deep background.
I call him Deep Throat.

971
01:00:20,409 --> 01:00:24,037
BEN: Look, McGovern's dropped to nothing,
Nixon's guaranteed the renomination...

972
01:00:24,205 --> 01:00:26,372
...the Post is stuck
with a story no one wants.

973
01:00:26,540 --> 01:00:29,459
It'll sink the goddamn paper.
Everyone says, "Get off it, Ben."

974
01:00:29,627 --> 01:00:31,403
And I come on very sage
and I say,

975
01:00:31,404 --> 01:00:33,379
"You'll see.
You wait till this bottoms out."

976
01:00:33,547 --> 01:00:37,383
But the truth is,
I can't figure out what we've got.

977
01:00:39,720 --> 01:00:41,054
What else are you working on?

978
01:00:41,222 --> 01:00:43,223
Well, we're after a list
of CREEP employees.

979
01:00:43,390 --> 01:00:45,600
BEN: Where is it?
- It's classified.

980
01:00:45,768 --> 01:00:48,937
BEN: Well, how you gonna get it?
- We haven't had any luck yet.

981
01:00:49,396 --> 01:00:50,897
Get some.

982
01:00:55,945 --> 01:00:57,237
Anything else?

983
01:00:58,906 --> 01:01:00,907
[ELEVATOR DINGS]

984
01:01:07,373 --> 01:01:09,541
You made a mistake in there.

985
01:01:12,920 --> 01:01:14,295
What?

986
01:01:14,463 --> 01:01:17,674
You said we haven't had any luck yet,
that's the thing he jumps on.

987
01:01:17,842 --> 01:01:19,050
You can't talk about luck.

988
01:01:19,218 --> 01:01:22,095
If you can't talk in specifics,
you shouldn't say anything.

989
01:01:28,102 --> 01:01:30,061
Is there any place you don't smoke?

990
01:01:30,229 --> 01:01:32,230
[ELEVATOR DINGS]

991
01:01:32,982 --> 01:01:34,607
- What?
- Hold it. Hold it.

992
01:01:34,775 --> 01:01:36,901
- What are you doing?
BOB: Kay Eddy.

993
01:01:37,069 --> 01:01:40,196
Doesn't she go with a guy
that works for the Committee to Reelect?

994
01:01:40,364 --> 01:01:41,781
KAY: Meet me at 4.
MAN: All right.

995
01:01:41,949 --> 01:01:43,408
BOB: Eddy? Hey.
- Just a second.

996
01:01:43,576 --> 01:01:46,744
BOB: Kay, can...?
- 757-6521.

997
01:01:46,912 --> 01:01:49,706
Okay, I'll get back to you on this.
Thanks.

998
01:01:49,874 --> 01:01:53,459
BOB: Don't you go with a guy that works
for the Committee to Reelect?

999
01:01:54,336 --> 01:01:56,296
- Not anymore.
CARL: You did go with him, though.

1000
01:01:56,463 --> 01:01:59,090
- You were engaged to him, weren't you?
- Yeah.

1001
01:01:59,258 --> 01:02:01,134
You got out of it?

1002
01:02:01,802 --> 01:02:03,970
- So?
- You're looking better.

1003
01:02:04,138 --> 01:02:06,139
[ALL LAUGHING]

1004
01:02:07,057 --> 01:02:09,142
We need a list of the people
that work there.

1005
01:02:09,310 --> 01:02:10,810
Do you think that...?

1006
01:02:10,978 --> 01:02:13,897
- I can't do that.
CARL: Why not?

1007
01:02:14,064 --> 01:02:15,148
That's personal.

1008
01:02:15,316 --> 01:02:17,942
What do you mean? You said it was over.

1009
01:02:20,654 --> 01:02:23,114
You're asking me
to use a guy I care about.

1010
01:02:23,282 --> 01:02:25,950
CARL: No, no, we're not asking you
to use him, just to help us.

1011
01:02:26,118 --> 01:02:28,494
- Well, sure you...
CARL: I mean, we'd do the same for you.

1012
01:02:28,662 --> 01:02:30,830
My only chance of getting that
is if I see him.

1013
01:02:30,998 --> 01:02:33,791
- I don't wanna see him again.
- Well, do you have to see him?

1014
01:02:33,959 --> 01:02:36,294
- Sure, I have to.
- Do you have to see him that way?

1015
01:02:36,462 --> 01:02:37,795
Can't you just call him up...

1016
01:02:37,963 --> 01:02:40,840
...and say you wanna have a drink with him,
just feel him out?

1017
01:02:41,008 --> 01:02:44,594
You say the relationship is over.
I mean, what the hell do you have to lose?

1018
01:02:45,554 --> 01:02:47,180
Forget it.

1019
01:02:47,640 --> 01:02:49,682
Don't do anything
that would embarrass you...

1020
01:02:49,850 --> 01:02:52,268
...or that you don't feel right about.

1021
01:02:53,103 --> 01:02:54,729
Forget it.

1022
01:02:55,689 --> 01:02:57,190
Let's go.

1023
01:03:03,280 --> 01:03:06,199
CARL: Don't let her get off like that.
She was gonna say something.

1024
01:03:06,367 --> 01:03:07,533
You're overdramatizing.

1025
01:03:07,701 --> 01:03:10,078
- She was gonna give us what we wanted.
- It was over.

1026
01:03:10,245 --> 01:03:11,955
CARL: What?
BOB: It was over.

1027
01:03:17,044 --> 01:03:19,837
This looks like your story.
Why don't you take a look at it?

1028
01:03:20,005 --> 01:03:22,048
I'm gonna check this out.

1029
01:03:25,886 --> 01:03:28,888
WOMAN: You're gonna get fat
eating all those doughnuts.

1030
01:03:56,583 --> 01:03:59,085
CARL: Is this the whole list?
BOB: Look what it says.

1031
01:03:59,253 --> 01:04:02,588
"Personnel,
Committee to Reelect the President."

1032
01:04:03,632 --> 01:04:04,674
CARL:
This is alphabetical.

1033
01:04:04,842 --> 01:04:07,719
- You can't tell who works for who.
BOB: Find the department heads:

1034
01:04:07,886 --> 01:04:09,512
Mitchell, Magruder, Stans.

1035
01:04:09,680 --> 01:04:10,930
CARL:
Here. John Mitchell.

1036
01:04:11,098 --> 01:04:12,265
BOB: What's the number?
CARL: 301.

1037
01:04:12,433 --> 01:04:15,435
BOB: All right, find somebody
who has a number close to it.

1038
01:04:15,602 --> 01:04:18,104
- They probably work for him. Okay.
CARL: Here's a 303.

1039
01:04:20,858 --> 01:04:24,152
CARL: Okay, we have to find out how
the money got from Stans to the burglars.

1040
01:04:24,319 --> 01:04:26,738
BOB:
Somebody who worked in Finance.

1041
01:04:27,114 --> 01:04:29,949
CARL: All right, here's the head
of Finance. Maurice Stans, 269.

1042
01:04:30,117 --> 01:04:33,703
BOB: If we can just get somebody
who works under Stans.

1043
01:04:34,079 --> 01:04:35,955
CARL: Uh, Sloan? You need him?
BOB: He's the treasurer.

1044
01:04:36,123 --> 01:04:38,041
- What's the number?
CARL: It's Hugh Sloan, 287.

1045
01:04:38,208 --> 01:04:39,876
BOB:
Is there a secretary?

1046
01:04:41,253 --> 01:04:44,464
- Wait a minute. Manley, Manley, Manley.
CARL: Here it is. Irene Manley?

1047
01:04:44,631 --> 01:04:47,967
BOB: Yeah.
CARL: 1406 Lee Jackson Memorial Highway.

1048
01:04:48,343 --> 01:04:50,303
BOB: Hi, I'm Bob Woodward.
CARL: I'm Carl Bernstein.

1049
01:04:50,471 --> 01:04:53,431
BOB: We're from the Washington Post.
We'd like to speak to you.

1050
01:04:53,599 --> 01:04:56,476
We understand your daughter works
for the Committee to Reelect.

1051
01:04:56,643 --> 01:04:59,604
CARL: Wouldn't be anything embarrassing.
BOB: Would you object to just...?

1052
01:04:59,772 --> 01:05:01,064
MAN:
Forget it.

1053
01:05:02,066 --> 01:05:03,107
- Yes? Hi.
CARL: Hi.

1054
01:05:03,275 --> 01:05:04,650
BOB: Miss Milland? Betty Milland?
- Mm-hm.

1055
01:05:04,818 --> 01:05:06,611
BOB: I'm Bob Woodward.
CARL: Carl Bernstein.

1056
01:05:06,779 --> 01:05:08,237
We're from the Washington Post.

1057
01:05:08,405 --> 01:05:10,990
I know you're trying to do your job.
I mean...

1058
01:05:11,700 --> 01:05:13,826
You don't understand
the pressure we're under.

1059
01:05:13,994 --> 01:05:16,996
- If we could come in for a couple
seconds... - No, I really don't...

1060
01:05:17,164 --> 01:05:18,206
We don't wanna come in.

1061
01:05:18,373 --> 01:05:22,376
We understand there was some documents
that were shredded at the committee.

1062
01:05:22,544 --> 01:05:24,128
Well, there, uh...

1063
01:05:24,296 --> 01:05:26,589
There's often shredding.
I mean, we do that a lot.

1064
01:05:26,757 --> 01:05:28,466
Were you there during the shredding?

1065
01:05:28,634 --> 01:05:29,884
- Yes, I was.
- I see.

1066
01:05:30,052 --> 01:05:33,554
Were there any department heads
from the committee who were also present?

1067
01:05:33,722 --> 01:05:36,599
Uh, yes. Mr. Mitchell came in one night.

1068
01:05:36,767 --> 01:05:37,809
BOB: John Mitchell?
- Yes.

1069
01:05:37,976 --> 01:05:39,185
- The attorney general?
- Uh-huh.

1070
01:05:39,353 --> 01:05:42,021
He was carrying a raincoat over his head.

1071
01:05:42,189 --> 01:05:44,023
You know, because he was...
I thought he was gonna go:

1072
01:05:44,191 --> 01:05:45,483
Woo-hoo. Woo-hoo.

1073
01:05:45,651 --> 01:05:48,111
- But, uh, I...
- Did he supervise the shredding?

1074
01:05:48,278 --> 01:05:50,363
Uh, I just...
Can I not answer any more questions?

1075
01:05:50,531 --> 01:05:53,449
I'd just as soon not...
Okay? Maybe I could call you.

1076
01:05:53,617 --> 01:05:56,369
CARL: It's...
- Are you being told not to talk?

1077
01:05:57,121 --> 01:06:00,623
CARL: Will you call us?
- I don't know.

1078
01:06:00,791 --> 01:06:01,958
I'll try.

1079
01:06:02,126 --> 01:06:04,460
What about that shredding
right after the break-in?

1080
01:06:04,628 --> 01:06:06,629
We need to know the papers
in the shredding.

1081
01:06:06,797 --> 01:06:10,383
You have some idea what's in the papers
when the attorney general comes in...

1082
01:06:10,551 --> 01:06:13,511
...it's at the committee,
and he's got a raincoat over his head.

1083
01:06:13,679 --> 01:06:16,347
It could be raining.
Let me go through the story again.

1084
01:06:16,515 --> 01:06:18,766
You got a woman who's frightened.
Works for CREEP.

1085
01:06:18,934 --> 01:06:21,894
She said there's shredding.
We don't know what's in the papers.

1086
01:06:22,062 --> 01:06:25,565
We know the former attorney general
comes in with an overcoat over his head.

1087
01:06:25,732 --> 01:06:29,318
Could be raining. There's a lawyer present.
We don't know what he asked them.

1088
01:06:29,486 --> 01:06:31,320
Will you tell me where there's a story?

1089
01:06:31,488 --> 01:06:34,490
In the fact that the interview
did not take place in her home...

1090
01:06:34,658 --> 01:06:36,409
...but in the office of the committee.

1091
01:06:36,577 --> 01:06:40,246
- How is there a story in that?
- Because there's a lawyer in the office.

1092
01:06:40,414 --> 01:06:42,707
- You're more resistant than she is.
- That's right.

1093
01:06:42,875 --> 01:06:45,376
- Why?
- Because there's not enough fact.

1094
01:06:45,544 --> 01:06:48,754
CARL: Well, then let's just turn around
and go back and question her again.

1095
01:06:50,716 --> 01:06:53,593
- This won't take long at all. We just...
- Please go away, okay?

1096
01:06:53,760 --> 01:06:56,512
Will you please leave
before they see you?

1097
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:59,640
- Who did you mean by...?
- What do you mean, "they"?

1098
01:06:59,808 --> 01:07:01,392
Could you give us their names?

1099
01:07:01,560 --> 01:07:05,563
CARL: We haven't revealed the sources
of the people that have talked to us.

1100
01:07:05,981 --> 01:07:10,443
- I really can't talk about this because...
- Would they be members of the committee?

1101
01:07:13,280 --> 01:07:15,114
CARL:
Someone got to that woman.

1102
01:07:15,282 --> 01:07:16,908
It's the key to the whole cover-up.

1103
01:07:17,075 --> 01:07:20,119
BOB: How can you write there's a cover-up?
We don't know that there is.

1104
01:07:20,287 --> 01:07:24,582
Then I don't know what the hell you need.
So you tell me what you need.

1105
01:07:25,167 --> 01:07:28,294
BOB: I need more fact for a story,
and I think you should need the same.

1106
01:07:28,462 --> 01:07:30,963
CARL: if you get in a car and
there's music... - I'm in a car.

1107
01:07:31,131 --> 01:07:33,424
There's music playing in the car...
Hypothetically.

1108
01:07:33,592 --> 01:07:36,469
There's music playing for 10 minutes
and there's no commercial.

1109
01:07:36,637 --> 01:07:38,054
What can you deduce from that?

1110
01:07:38,222 --> 01:07:39,388
- Is it AM or FM?
- Come on.

1111
01:07:39,556 --> 01:07:40,640
Is it AM or FM?

1112
01:07:40,807 --> 01:07:44,852
A guy can come up to me on the street,
and he can ask me an address.

1113
01:07:45,020 --> 01:07:47,813
Now, is the man interrogating me,
or is he lost?

1114
01:07:47,981 --> 01:07:49,482
What kind of a story do I write?

1115
01:07:49,650 --> 01:07:51,692
What kind of a deduction
do I make from that?

1116
01:07:51,860 --> 01:07:54,862
CARL: You don't have a gut feeling
that the woman is trying to help us?

1117
01:07:55,030 --> 01:07:57,657
BOB: I don't have enough gut feeling.
I wish I did.

1118
01:07:58,659 --> 01:08:01,160
BOB:
We're from the Washington Post.

1119
01:08:02,412 --> 01:08:04,163
Ammons, Irene Ammons. Did we see her?

1120
01:08:05,332 --> 01:08:09,502
Abbott, Addison, Augusto, Alberte.

1121
01:08:16,885 --> 01:08:19,387
Is there something that strikes you
as odd about this?

1122
01:08:19,554 --> 01:08:21,305
CARL: What?
BOB: It's like there's a pattern...

1123
01:08:21,473 --> 01:08:24,600
...to the way they're not talking,
the way they say no all the time.

1124
01:08:24,768 --> 01:08:25,977
I think it's odd.

1125
01:08:26,353 --> 01:08:27,895
- Mrs. Hambling?
- Yes.

1126
01:08:28,063 --> 01:08:32,650
- Hi, we're from the Washington Post.
- I'm Carl Bernstein, this is Bob Woodward.

1127
01:08:32,818 --> 01:08:35,695
BOB: A friend of the committee
said that we could contact you.

1128
01:08:35,862 --> 01:08:37,905
- Who was it?
- We can't reveal that.

1129
01:08:38,073 --> 01:08:40,366
You can talk to us.
We don't reveal our sources.

1130
01:08:40,534 --> 01:08:42,576
You people.

1131
01:08:43,036 --> 01:08:46,831
You think you can come into my home,
ask a few questions...

1132
01:08:46,999 --> 01:08:52,336
...have me destroy the reputations
of men that I work for and respect?

1133
01:08:53,171 --> 01:08:55,381
Do you understand loyalty?

1134
01:08:55,549 --> 01:08:58,050
Have you ever heard of loyalty?

1135
01:08:58,677 --> 01:09:00,303
BOB & CARL: Hi.
- Yes?

1136
01:09:00,470 --> 01:09:02,054
BOB: I'm Bob Woodward.
CARL: Carl Bernstein.

1137
01:09:02,222 --> 01:09:04,640
- We're from the Washington Post.
- Yes.

1138
01:09:04,808 --> 01:09:08,102
I've read what you've written.
I wanna thank you.

1139
01:09:08,562 --> 01:09:11,897
I've been a Republican all my life,
but this goes beyond party politics.

1140
01:09:12,065 --> 01:09:14,525
Would you mind
if we asked you a few questions?

1141
01:09:14,693 --> 01:09:16,861
No, no. Come in. Would you like coffee?

1142
01:09:18,196 --> 01:09:19,613
Sure.

1143
01:09:19,781 --> 01:09:22,533
What they've done
is a threat to the Constitution.

1144
01:09:22,701 --> 01:09:24,827
It goes against everything we stand for.

1145
01:09:24,995 --> 01:09:27,830
Could you be a little bit more specific
than that?

1146
01:09:28,165 --> 01:09:30,791
I'm afraid your articles
have just scratched the surface.

1147
01:09:30,959 --> 01:09:33,586
You don't mind
if I just take a few notes, do you?

1148
01:09:33,754 --> 01:09:35,212
No.

1149
01:09:35,922 --> 01:09:38,466
How long have you worked
at the committee?

1150
01:09:38,633 --> 01:09:39,675
Committee?

1151
01:09:39,843 --> 01:09:43,554
Yes, the Committee
to Reelect the President.

1152
01:09:44,306 --> 01:09:48,100
Oh. Oh, no, I don't work
at the Committee to Reelect the President.

1153
01:09:48,268 --> 01:09:52,897
I work at Garfinckel's,
in the Accounting Department.

1154
01:09:55,901 --> 01:09:58,778
- Miss Abbott?
- Yes.

1155
01:09:59,321 --> 01:10:01,113
Judith Abbott?

1156
01:10:03,200 --> 01:10:05,618
Carolyn Abbott.

1157
01:10:07,746 --> 01:10:10,039
We're just doing something wrong.

1158
01:10:12,793 --> 01:10:15,336
- It's never been there.
- No.

1159
01:10:15,712 --> 01:10:17,838
We're doing something wrong.

1160
01:10:18,465 --> 01:10:20,549
It's just not good enough.

1161
01:10:20,967 --> 01:10:24,303
How can you keep going at something
past the point when you'd believe it?

1162
01:10:24,471 --> 01:10:26,472
Just have to start all over again.

1163
01:10:32,312 --> 01:10:35,106
CARL:
Nasemith, Narrow, Ness...

1164
01:10:35,273 --> 01:10:37,441
...Nickels, Nixon...

1165
01:10:37,609 --> 01:10:39,485
BOB:
Ed Nixon.

1166
01:10:39,653 --> 01:10:42,571
Jolson, Jones...

1167
01:10:42,739 --> 01:10:44,740
...Jordan, Jost.

1168
01:10:44,908 --> 01:10:48,160
If we could only get somebody
that worked for Finance to talk.

1169
01:10:48,328 --> 01:10:50,079
- What about the bookkeeper?
CARL: Which?

1170
01:10:50,247 --> 01:10:52,373
BOB: The bookkeeper that worked
for both Slans and...

1171
01:10:52,541 --> 01:10:54,375
CARL: Oh, you're all right.
BOB: Sloan and Stans.

1172
01:10:54,543 --> 01:10:57,336
CARL: I've been there. I've called her
twice. There's no answer.

1173
01:10:57,504 --> 01:10:59,713
BOB:
I say we should start again.

1174
01:11:00,215 --> 01:11:04,343
Abbott, Addison, Augusto, Alberte...

1175
01:11:04,511 --> 01:11:07,263
...Aldus, Alessandro...

1176
01:11:07,431 --> 01:11:10,850
CARL:
Eulosky, Clan, Constell...

1177
01:11:11,017 --> 01:11:15,146
BOB:
Boyle, Brenner, Bromley, Jost...

1178
01:11:15,313 --> 01:11:19,442
CARL:
Nasemith, Narrow, Ness, Nickels...

1179
01:11:19,609 --> 01:11:22,528
BOB:
Teeny, Sandstrom...

1180
01:11:23,947 --> 01:11:26,991
Skroes, Skully...

1181
01:11:27,159 --> 01:11:29,660
CARL:
Skully. We've been there twice.

1182
01:11:30,745 --> 01:11:34,498
All right, Wilcox, Winthrow,
Windsor, Worts...

1183
01:11:35,041 --> 01:11:38,043
Two weeks work, half the names
crossed off and what have you got?

1184
01:11:38,211 --> 01:11:39,795
BOB:
People aren't talking, Harry.

1185
01:11:39,963 --> 01:11:42,631
And it's the way they're not talking
that's unnatural.

1186
01:11:42,799 --> 01:11:46,051
We've been up all night. We went
over all the quotes of the people...

1187
01:11:46,219 --> 01:11:48,554
BOB: It's like they're getting
instructions. It's pat.

1188
01:11:48,722 --> 01:11:51,015
You wanna hear some real news?

1189
01:11:51,183 --> 01:11:53,434
That GAO report
in which you placed so much faith?

1190
01:11:53,602 --> 01:11:56,103
It's been postponed
till after tonight's renomination.

1191
01:11:56,271 --> 01:11:58,731
- What do you mean?
- Hughes got a call from Stans.

1192
01:11:58,899 --> 01:12:01,567
Says he has new information,
not to republish without it.

1193
01:12:01,735 --> 01:12:04,403
They're gonna bury the report
till after the renomination.

1194
01:12:04,571 --> 01:12:06,071
The indictment will be out soon.

1195
01:12:06,239 --> 01:12:10,493
Every indication says the indictment will
stop at the five burglars, Hunt and Liddy.

1196
01:12:10,660 --> 01:12:13,120
And that's the end of your story.

1197
01:12:17,584 --> 01:12:21,670
FORD [ON TV]: The vote of all the delegates
has been recorded.

1198
01:12:23,215 --> 01:12:27,051
The vote for Richard Nixon...

1199
01:12:28,345 --> 01:12:31,722
...is 1347.

1200
01:12:32,974 --> 01:12:37,436
The vote for Paul McCloskey is 1.

1201
01:12:39,564 --> 01:12:45,027
And therefore I declare the nominee
of the Republican Party...

1202
01:12:45,195 --> 01:12:48,405
...for president of the United States...

1203
01:12:48,573 --> 01:12:51,033
...President Richard Nixon.

1204
01:12:51,201 --> 01:12:53,911
[CROWD CHEERING ON TV]

1205
01:12:56,289 --> 01:13:02,545
CROWD [CHANTING]: Four more years!
Four more years! Four more years!

1206
01:13:17,978 --> 01:13:23,983
ANNOUNCER: The president and the future
president of the United States of America.

1207
01:13:24,651 --> 01:13:26,819
NIXON:
Wonderful young faces I see out here.

1208
01:13:26,987 --> 01:13:31,365
Your enthusiasm, your idealism,
your hard work.

1209
01:13:31,533 --> 01:13:33,993
This is your first vote...

1210
01:13:34,160 --> 01:13:37,705
...and years from now,
I just hope you can all look back...

1211
01:13:37,872 --> 01:13:40,749
...and say it was one of your best votes.
Thank you.

1212
01:13:40,917 --> 01:13:42,918
[CROWD CHEERING ON TV]

1213
01:13:43,211 --> 01:13:48,007
CROWD [CHANTING]: Four more years!
Four more years! Four more years!

1214
01:14:05,859 --> 01:14:08,027
Hi, I'm Carl Bernstein
of the Washington Post.

1215
01:14:08,194 --> 01:14:10,571
I just wanna ask you
a couple of questions.

1216
01:14:10,739 --> 01:14:13,157
WOMAN 1: Well, you don't want me,
you want my sister.

1217
01:14:13,325 --> 01:14:15,534
It's for you. It's Carl Bernstein.

1218
01:14:15,702 --> 01:14:17,661
WOMAN 2 [WHISPERS]:
He's the guy from the Post. Get rid of him.

1219
01:14:17,829 --> 01:14:20,080
Could I just borrow
one of your cigarettes there?

1220
01:14:20,248 --> 01:14:21,665
Sure.

1221
01:14:22,709 --> 01:14:27,004
- You've really gotta go.
CARL: Sure. Could I just get a match?

1222
01:14:27,422 --> 01:14:28,881
I understand your being afraid.

1223
01:14:29,049 --> 01:14:30,716
There's a lot of people like you...

1224
01:14:30,884 --> 01:14:34,219
...who wanted to tell the truth,
but some people wouldn't listen.

1225
01:14:34,888 --> 01:14:38,223
Certain people have gone back
to the prosecutors and the FBI...

1226
01:14:38,391 --> 01:14:40,893
...to give information
which they were never asked.

1227
01:14:42,854 --> 01:14:46,565
You were Hugh Sloan's bookkeeper when
he worked for Maurice Stans up at Finance.

1228
01:14:46,733 --> 01:14:50,361
We were just wondering
if you were promoted...

1229
01:14:50,528 --> 01:14:53,280
...to work for Mr. Stans
immediately after Mr. Sloan quit...

1230
01:14:53,448 --> 01:14:56,784
...or whether there was some time lapse.

1231
01:14:59,829 --> 01:15:03,415
I never worked for Sloan or Stans.

1232
01:15:04,834 --> 01:15:08,170
Uh, can I get you some coffee
or something?

1233
01:15:08,338 --> 01:15:10,255
CARL:
Yeah, thanks very much.

1234
01:15:12,592 --> 01:15:14,218
[DOOR BELLS JINGLE]

1235
01:15:14,386 --> 01:15:16,095
Door sticks.

1236
01:15:18,431 --> 01:15:22,893
Uh, could I just sit down for a second?

1237
01:15:24,979 --> 01:15:28,273
Sure, you can sit down,
but I'm not going to tell you anything.

1238
01:15:29,943 --> 01:15:31,360
Okay.

1239
01:15:52,632 --> 01:15:55,592
I was just curious why you lied just then.

1240
01:15:55,760 --> 01:15:57,886
Have you been threatened
if you tell the truth?

1241
01:15:59,848 --> 01:16:01,348
No.

1242
01:16:02,142 --> 01:16:03,434
Never in so many words.

1243
01:16:04,477 --> 01:16:06,311
WOMAN 1: How do you like it?
- Just milk, thanks.

1244
01:16:06,479 --> 01:16:08,063
WOMAN 1:
Okay, I'll just get the milk.

1245
01:16:08,231 --> 01:16:12,067
Um, I saw in the wires
that Mrs. Stans was in the hospital.

1246
01:16:12,235 --> 01:16:13,318
Is she feeling better?

1247
01:16:19,242 --> 01:16:21,827
The GAO,
the General Accounting report...

1248
01:16:21,995 --> 01:16:24,663
...said that there was $350,000...

1249
01:16:24,831 --> 01:16:28,834
...in the safe
of the Committee to Reelect the President.

1250
01:16:29,002 --> 01:16:32,337
Were you aware that it was that kind
of funds from the very beginning?

1251
01:16:37,260 --> 01:16:40,721
A lot of people are watching me.
They know I know a lot.

1252
01:16:40,889 --> 01:16:45,142
- Was it all in $100 bills?
- A lot of it was.

1253
01:16:45,977 --> 01:16:48,520
I thought it was
an all-purpose political fund...

1254
01:16:48,688 --> 01:16:51,732
...you know, for taking fat cats to dinner,
things like that.

1255
01:16:51,900 --> 01:16:54,193
Three hundred and fifty thousand dollars
for dinners?

1256
01:16:54,360 --> 01:16:56,361
[CHUCKLES]

1257
01:16:56,529 --> 01:16:58,822
How was it paid out?

1258
01:17:02,827 --> 01:17:05,245
Not in one big chunk.

1259
01:17:06,372 --> 01:17:08,290
There was a list of 15 names...

1260
01:17:08,458 --> 01:17:12,002
...and the amount of money
given to each person next to the name.

1261
01:17:12,170 --> 01:17:14,463
What happened to the list?

1262
01:17:16,049 --> 01:17:17,674
It was destroyed.

1263
01:17:17,842 --> 01:17:19,718
It was the only record.

1264
01:17:20,595 --> 01:17:24,181
This... Don't pay any attention to this.
This is just for my memory.

1265
01:17:24,349 --> 01:17:25,933
Hate the...

1266
01:17:26,559 --> 01:17:29,228
I have a very bad memory.

1267
01:17:30,063 --> 01:17:31,605
You won't be quoted by name.

1268
01:17:31,773 --> 01:17:34,983
In fact, we get confirmations
before we print anything.

1269
01:17:35,151 --> 01:17:39,863
I can't be positive that that money
was used for the break-in, you understand?

1270
01:17:40,031 --> 01:17:41,573
Yes, I do.

1271
01:17:41,741 --> 01:17:45,619
- But people sure are worried.
- Which people?

1272
01:17:51,501 --> 01:17:55,379
Think you could help me
with the disbursement of money...

1273
01:17:55,547 --> 01:17:58,173
...in terms of the number of people
that were involved?

1274
01:17:58,341 --> 01:17:59,883
How many?

1275
01:18:02,011 --> 01:18:04,513
A group of them. About five.
I don't know their names.

1276
01:18:04,681 --> 01:18:08,392
Would Mr. Sloan know?

1277
01:18:10,937 --> 01:18:12,104
WOMAN 1:
Here you are.

1278
01:18:12,272 --> 01:18:16,316
- Would he have any...?
- I don't wanna say anymore, okay?

1279
01:18:23,032 --> 01:18:26,994
Um, I won't be much longer.

1280
01:18:28,830 --> 01:18:33,709
I wonder if you could just help me
a little bit about the money.

1281
01:18:33,877 --> 01:18:36,628
We hear all kinds of figures.

1282
01:18:39,799 --> 01:18:43,343
- There was so much of it.
- How much is "so much"?

1283
01:18:43,511 --> 01:18:47,306
In one two-day period,
6 million dollars came in.

1284
01:18:48,057 --> 01:18:50,559
- Six.
- Six million, cash.

1285
01:18:50,727 --> 01:18:52,185
CARL:
Mm-hm.

1286
01:18:52,854 --> 01:18:55,480
- We didn't know where to put it all.
- Heh.

1287
01:18:56,274 --> 01:18:57,524
I thought it was all legal.

1288
01:18:57,692 --> 01:19:00,485
I mean, I guess I did
until after the break-in...

1289
01:19:00,653 --> 01:19:02,779
...when I remembered
Gordon got so much of it.

1290
01:19:02,947 --> 01:19:06,491
- This is Mr. Liddy?
- It's all so rotten.

1291
01:19:07,327 --> 01:19:09,328
It's getting worse.

1292
01:19:09,996 --> 01:19:12,915
And the only one I care about
is Hugh Sloan.

1293
01:19:13,082 --> 01:19:17,169
His wife was going to leave him if he
didn't stand up and do what was right.

1294
01:19:17,670 --> 01:19:18,837
So he quit.

1295
01:19:20,548 --> 01:19:22,174
I was wondering...

1296
01:19:23,968 --> 01:19:29,681
...if Hugh Sloan was being set up now
as a fall guy for John Mitchell.

1297
01:19:30,099 --> 01:19:31,516
What do you think?

1298
01:19:34,812 --> 01:19:37,606
[SIGHS]

1299
01:19:39,400 --> 01:19:43,362
If you guys could get John Mitchell,
that would be beautiful.

1300
01:19:51,329 --> 01:19:52,454
Coffee's cold.

1301
01:19:54,749 --> 01:19:56,750
Is there any evidence...

1302
01:19:57,710 --> 01:20:01,129
...that any of Mr. Mitchell's assistants...

1303
01:20:02,256 --> 01:20:03,465
...were part of this?

1304
01:20:04,175 --> 01:20:08,220
I had all the evidence. It was destroyed.
I don't know who destroyed it.

1305
01:20:08,388 --> 01:20:11,431
- I think Gordon did a lot of shredding.
- Hard evidence?

1306
01:20:11,599 --> 01:20:15,686
Well, I can't say that it would positively
prove that they planned the break-in...

1307
01:20:15,853 --> 01:20:17,896
...but it would come pretty close.

1308
01:20:18,064 --> 01:20:22,025
Can you tell me anything, anything,
about who got the money?

1309
01:20:23,152 --> 01:20:28,740
We have had some help on this
from a couple sources...

1310
01:20:28,908 --> 01:20:31,576
...and this is a way of confirming it.

1311
01:20:35,039 --> 01:20:39,209
I don't want you to feel you're in a
position where you have to disclose names.

1312
01:20:39,377 --> 01:20:42,170
You know, I can just ask you initials...

1313
01:20:42,338 --> 01:20:46,216
...and then that way
you're not divulging any information.

1314
01:20:46,384 --> 01:20:49,386
We have some idea.
Would that be all right?

1315
01:20:49,887 --> 01:20:51,888
[SIGHS]

1316
01:20:54,142 --> 01:20:56,101
Was there an M?

1317
01:20:58,938 --> 01:21:00,605
Can you just nod either way?

1318
01:21:02,358 --> 01:21:04,401
Did it go that high up?

1319
01:21:08,239 --> 01:21:09,740
L? Hm.

1320
01:21:11,534 --> 01:21:13,076
I don't wanna say any more, okay?

1321
01:21:13,244 --> 01:21:16,246
I'm sorry, you said L or...?

1322
01:21:16,414 --> 01:21:20,333
I get confused.
Could we just go back for a second?

1323
01:21:20,877 --> 01:21:23,003
CARL: In one six-day period,
over $6 million came in.

1324
01:21:23,171 --> 01:21:25,464
Wouldn't believe what was going on
in that woman.

1325
01:21:25,631 --> 01:21:29,134
Stuff was ready to pour out of her.
I'm pouring down coffee to get it out...

1326
01:21:29,302 --> 01:21:30,594
...before she throws me out.

1327
01:21:30,762 --> 01:21:32,846
- Give me your notes so...
- These are the notes.

1328
01:21:33,014 --> 01:21:35,015
- These?
- I got stuff on napkins, matchbooks.

1329
01:21:35,183 --> 01:21:37,726
I'm writing in the bathroom
while she's getting coffee.

1330
01:21:37,894 --> 01:21:39,061
You're crazy. How am I...?

1331
01:21:39,228 --> 01:21:42,230
You'd be crazy too if you were operating
on 20 cups of coffee.

1332
01:21:42,398 --> 01:21:46,234
- Give me something I can get down.
- I got it. I got it all. Okay. Write.

1333
01:21:46,402 --> 01:21:49,196
- Mitchell was in control.
- Wait a minute.

1334
01:21:49,655 --> 01:21:51,948
- There were men working under Mitchell.
- How many?

1335
01:21:52,116 --> 01:21:55,827
I don't know, but the men under Mitchell
received the money from the slush fund.

1336
01:21:55,995 --> 01:21:59,164
- Do we know how much money?
- Yeah, hundreds of thousands of dollars.

1337
01:21:59,332 --> 01:22:02,084
And these men are the key
to what that money was used for.

1338
01:22:02,251 --> 01:22:03,585
Boy, that woman was paranoid.

1339
01:22:03,753 --> 01:22:06,671
At one point, I suddenly wondered
how high up this thing goes...

1340
01:22:06,839 --> 01:22:08,632
...and her paranoia finally got to me.

1341
01:22:08,800 --> 01:22:12,260
I thought what we had was so hot
that CBS or NBC were gonna take the story.

1342
01:22:12,428 --> 01:22:13,470
You're both paranoid.

1343
01:22:13,638 --> 01:22:16,348
She's afraid of Mitchell,
you're afraid of Walter Cronkite.

1344
01:22:16,516 --> 01:22:18,683
- Can we go back to what she said?
- Yeah.

1345
01:22:20,103 --> 01:22:22,896
Here. L, P and M.

1346
01:22:23,815 --> 01:22:25,190
- What do you mean?
- L, P and M.

1347
01:22:25,358 --> 01:22:27,192
- She'd only give me initials.
- Initials?

1348
01:22:27,360 --> 01:22:30,695
Yeah, the initials of the men
that worked under Mitchell: L, P and M.

1349
01:22:30,863 --> 01:22:32,864
You couldn't get the names?

1350
01:22:33,032 --> 01:22:34,241
[CARL SIGHS]

1351
01:22:34,408 --> 01:22:37,369
If I could've, I would've.
I'm trying to get anything I can.

1352
01:22:37,537 --> 01:22:39,746
She said L, P and M...
That's all she'd give me.

1353
01:22:39,914 --> 01:22:41,873
...are the people
who worked under Mitchell.

1354
01:22:42,041 --> 01:22:44,584
She said something about Mitchell.
She hates him.

1355
01:22:44,752 --> 01:22:46,294
- She said that?
- Here. She said:

1356
01:22:46,462 --> 01:22:49,381
"If you guys could get John Mitchell,
that would be beautiful."

1357
01:22:49,549 --> 01:22:51,049
What are you writing about Sloan?

1358
01:22:51,217 --> 01:22:53,635
- "Sloan was the treasurer."
- His wife did what?

1359
01:22:53,803 --> 01:22:57,556
"His wife is pregnant and made Sloan quit.
He no longer wanted to be part of it."

1360
01:22:57,723 --> 01:22:58,890
We've gotta go see Sloan.

1361
01:22:59,058 --> 01:23:00,767
- Okay, make a note of it.
- All right.

1362
01:23:00,935 --> 01:23:03,270
So, what have we got?
Where's that matchbook? Here.

1363
01:23:03,437 --> 01:23:05,522
- L, P and M.
- Okay, L, P and M.

1364
01:23:05,690 --> 01:23:08,400
- L could be LaRue. It could be Liddy.
- L is Liddy.

1365
01:23:08,568 --> 01:23:10,569
- How do we know that?
- Because she said it.

1366
01:23:10,736 --> 01:23:13,155
Right here, she said,
"At the time of the break-in...

1367
01:23:13,322 --> 01:23:16,199
...there was so much money
that I know Gordon got part of it."

1368
01:23:16,367 --> 01:23:19,161
I said, "You mean Gordon Liddy?"
She said yes. So L is Liddy.

1369
01:23:19,328 --> 01:23:20,912
- Right.
- Okay, that leaves P and M.

1370
01:23:21,080 --> 01:23:23,582
P could be Parkinson.

1371
01:23:23,749 --> 01:23:26,251
It could be Porter. It could be...

1372
01:23:26,419 --> 01:23:29,713
Wait a minute. There was a guy.
There was a guy we talked to last week.

1373
01:23:29,881 --> 01:23:33,216
Didn't he say there was a Bart Porter
who was a member of the committee?

1374
01:23:33,384 --> 01:23:36,970
- Porter was called before the grand jury.
- So P is definitely Porter.

1375
01:23:37,138 --> 01:23:38,430
P could be Porter.

1376
01:23:38,598 --> 01:23:41,933
P is Porter, L is Liddy. That leaves...
All that leaves is M.

1377
01:23:42,101 --> 01:23:44,728
M could be McCord. That's out.

1378
01:23:44,896 --> 01:23:47,689
It could be Mardian.

1379
01:23:47,857 --> 01:23:49,691
It could be...

1380
01:23:49,859 --> 01:23:51,568
- ...Magruder.
- I think it's Magruder.

1381
01:23:51,736 --> 01:23:54,404
- I think it's Magruder too.
- Why do you think it is?

1382
01:23:54,572 --> 01:23:56,948
He was second in command under Mitchell.
Why do you?

1383
01:23:57,116 --> 01:24:01,077
Because at one time, he was the temporary
head of the committee, before Mitchell.

1384
01:24:01,245 --> 01:24:05,081
I don't want a cookie. We've gotta get
that bookkeeper to say it was Magruder.

1385
01:24:05,249 --> 01:24:09,085
- Never get her to say anything but "M."
- We gotta go back and get her to say it.

1386
01:24:09,253 --> 01:24:12,339
If we can make names of the initials...

1387
01:24:12,506 --> 01:24:14,925
...we'll know the people
who paid off the burglars.

1388
01:24:15,092 --> 01:24:17,469
We'll at least know who got the money.

1389
01:24:19,138 --> 01:24:22,098
The indictments that came down
from the grand jury today...

1390
01:24:22,266 --> 01:24:26,311
...stop with the five burglars,
Hunt and Liddy.

1391
01:24:26,979 --> 01:24:30,899
Carl, we have got to go back there and get
that bookkeeper to say who the names are.

1392
01:24:31,067 --> 01:24:32,525
She ain't gonna give it to you.

1393
01:24:32,693 --> 01:24:35,153
- I was with the woman for six hours.
- We gotta try.

1394
01:24:35,321 --> 01:24:37,322
Then you have to trick her, threaten her.

1395
01:24:37,490 --> 01:24:40,200
- Wait, you know what we could do?
- What?

1396
01:24:43,329 --> 01:24:46,039
- Listen, we go back there...
- Yeah.

1397
01:24:46,207 --> 01:24:47,832
...and you ask her who P is.

1398
01:24:48,000 --> 01:24:49,084
- Yeah.
- And then I say:

1399
01:24:49,252 --> 01:24:51,628
"No, no, no, we know P is Porter."
I just bury it.

1400
01:24:51,796 --> 01:24:54,214
- Wait a minute. I say to her, "Who is P?"
- Right.

1401
01:24:54,382 --> 01:24:57,175
- Then you say to me...
- I say, "No, we know P is Porter."

1402
01:24:57,343 --> 01:24:59,010
- You try to fake her out?
- Right.

1403
01:24:59,178 --> 01:25:00,845
And what if she denies it?

1404
01:25:01,013 --> 01:25:02,180
- We're screwed.
- So?

1405
01:25:02,348 --> 01:25:06,518
- But if she doesn't, we know P is Porter.
- Try it.

1406
01:25:15,736 --> 01:25:18,613
- Hi.
- They'll see you.

1407
01:25:19,198 --> 01:25:21,533
Not if you let us in, they won't.

1408
01:25:21,701 --> 01:25:24,369
BOB: I'm Bob Woodward.
- They'll see your car.

1409
01:25:24,537 --> 01:25:27,163
CARL:
We parked around the corner.

1410
01:25:27,540 --> 01:25:30,250
You have answers for everything,
don't you?

1411
01:25:30,418 --> 01:25:32,961
BOB:
If we did, we wouldn't be here.

1412
01:25:35,047 --> 01:25:36,256
You wrote what I told you.

1413
01:25:36,424 --> 01:25:38,383
No, not your name.
No one knows it was you.

1414
01:25:38,551 --> 01:25:43,096
Could you tell us who got the money?
And how much?

1415
01:25:43,723 --> 01:25:47,142
You mean like,
"What did you do with the 25 grand, lady?"

1416
01:25:47,310 --> 01:25:48,727
What?

1417
01:25:49,312 --> 01:25:53,023
Little jokes they're making
down at Finance these days.

1418
01:25:53,399 --> 01:25:56,443
If people are to be convinced
that Stans and Sloan are innocent...

1419
01:25:56,610 --> 01:25:59,487
...then our reporting must be precise,
and you can help us.

1420
01:25:59,655 --> 01:26:01,573
- Who is P?
- P, we know, is Porter.

1421
01:26:01,741 --> 01:26:06,453
You said 25 grand.
Is that how much Porter got?

1422
01:26:10,249 --> 01:26:11,374
Was it more?

1423
01:26:16,589 --> 01:26:19,132
Was it more than $50,000?

1424
01:26:22,345 --> 01:26:24,846
Was Magruder the only M
to receive money?

1425
01:26:32,563 --> 01:26:34,230
Who told you about Porter?

1426
01:26:35,608 --> 01:26:36,649
[TYPEWRITER CLACKING]

1427
01:26:36,817 --> 01:26:41,279
WOMAN [ON TV]: I'd like to move on to the
subject of the break-in at the Watergate...

1428
01:26:41,447 --> 01:26:43,656
...and the controversies
coming up out of that.

1429
01:26:43,824 --> 01:26:47,160
It has recently, very recently,
been reported now...

1430
01:26:47,328 --> 01:26:51,664
...that some documents were torn up
at the Committee to Reelect the President.

1431
01:26:51,832 --> 01:26:54,626
Uh, are you investigating the tearing up
of those documents...?

1432
01:26:54,794 --> 01:26:57,462
KLEINDIENST: I think that came out
in the story in the Washington Post.

1433
01:26:57,630 --> 01:26:59,464
WOMAN: Yes.
KLEINDIENST: I think the investigation...

1434
01:26:59,632 --> 01:27:03,635
...that has just concluded itself has
probably been one of the most intensive...

1435
01:27:03,803 --> 01:27:07,639
...that the Department of Justice
and the FBI has ever been involved in.

1436
01:27:07,807 --> 01:27:09,891
Some 1500 persons were interviewed...

1437
01:27:10,059 --> 01:27:14,062
...1800 leads were followed,
333 agents were involved...

1438
01:27:14,230 --> 01:27:16,439
...14,000 man-hours.

1439
01:27:16,607 --> 01:27:21,486
Fifty-one of the 59 FBI field officers
were involved. Uh...

1440
01:27:21,654 --> 01:27:23,446
And that, I think...

1441
01:27:23,614 --> 01:27:27,492
...is a great credit
to justice in this country.

1442
01:27:27,660 --> 01:27:29,869
Did you know that documents
had been destroyed?

1443
01:27:30,037 --> 01:27:31,121
No, I did not.

1444
01:27:33,749 --> 01:27:37,669
CARL: All these neat little houses
on all these nice little streets.

1445
01:27:37,837 --> 01:27:40,547
It's hard to believe
that something's wrong...

1446
01:27:40,714 --> 01:27:42,590
...in some of those little houses.

1447
01:27:42,758 --> 01:27:44,426
BOB:
No, it isn't.

1448
01:27:45,803 --> 01:27:48,221
- Hello. I'm Bob Woodward.
- Hello. I'm Carl Bernstein.

1449
01:27:48,389 --> 01:27:51,099
We'd just like to talk to Mr. Sloan
for a couple minutes.

1450
01:27:51,267 --> 01:27:53,435
MRS. SLOAN: He's resting right now.
- Are you Mrs. Sloan?

1451
01:27:55,604 --> 01:27:58,523
- You're the two from the Post, aren't you?
BOB: Yes.

1452
01:27:59,442 --> 01:28:04,028
- This is an honest house.
- That's why we'd like to see your husband.

1453
01:28:04,447 --> 01:28:06,574
In the face of charges
that might be brought

1454
01:28:06,575 --> 01:28:08,700
against people that are
innocent, we feel...

1455
01:28:08,868 --> 01:28:10,160
It's really for his benefit.

1456
01:28:10,744 --> 01:28:12,704
No, it's not.

1457
01:28:15,458 --> 01:28:16,875
No.

1458
01:28:17,376 --> 01:28:19,627
- It's not.
SLOAN: Deborah?

1459
01:28:20,045 --> 01:28:22,380
- Tell them to come in.
CARL: Thanks.

1460
01:28:22,548 --> 01:28:24,757
- Hi. Carl Bernstein.
- How do you do? Hugh Sloan.

1461
01:28:24,925 --> 01:28:25,967
BOB:
Bob Woodward.

1462
01:28:26,135 --> 01:28:29,179
- How you doing? Hugh Sloan.
BOB: I appreciate you giving us the time.

1463
01:28:36,187 --> 01:28:40,315
You know, the reason we're here, basically,
is that we talked to certain people...

1464
01:28:40,483 --> 01:28:42,442
...who indicated you left the committee...

1465
01:28:42,610 --> 01:28:44,903
...because you no longer wanted
to be part of it.

1466
01:28:45,070 --> 01:28:46,946
Maybe there's a legitimate explanation...

1467
01:28:47,114 --> 01:28:50,408
...for why the money was handed
to Liddy and Mitchell's aides.

1468
01:28:53,662 --> 01:28:55,747
Try and understand this.

1469
01:28:56,916 --> 01:28:59,542
- I'm a Republican.
- I am too.

1470
01:28:59,710 --> 01:29:01,377
Well, I believe in Richard Nixon.

1471
01:29:01,545 --> 01:29:04,547
I worked in the White House for four years,
and so did my wife.

1472
01:29:04,715 --> 01:29:06,758
What happened on June 17th...

1473
01:29:06,926 --> 01:29:09,260
...I don't think the president
knew anything about.

1474
01:29:09,428 --> 01:29:11,763
CARL: Is it possible some of his people
might have known?

1475
01:29:11,931 --> 01:29:12,972
I'm not sure.

1476
01:29:13,140 --> 01:29:14,849
CARL:
Think the truth will come out at the trial?

1477
01:29:15,017 --> 01:29:17,143
- That's another thing I'm not sure about.
- Why?

1478
01:29:17,311 --> 01:29:19,854
Obviously because certain people
lie to the prosecutor.

1479
01:29:20,022 --> 01:29:22,106
No, we were never told flat-out,
"Don't talk."

1480
01:29:22,274 --> 01:29:24,108
But the message was clear, though.

1481
01:29:24,276 --> 01:29:27,028
In other words, by their very silence,
there was a cover-up.

1482
01:29:27,196 --> 01:29:29,781
They didn't urge us to come forward
and tell the truth.

1483
01:29:29,949 --> 01:29:32,116
"They" meaning the White House?

1484
01:29:32,284 --> 01:29:34,327
The committee's not
an independent operation.

1485
01:29:34,495 --> 01:29:36,412
Everything's cleared
with the White House.

1486
01:29:36,580 --> 01:29:39,707
And I don't think that the FBI
or the prosecutors understand that.

1487
01:29:39,875 --> 01:29:42,126
BOB:
That report on the cash...

1488
01:29:42,836 --> 01:29:46,297
...in the CREEP safe, that...
What was it?... $350,000, is that a...?

1489
01:29:46,465 --> 01:29:49,217
- No, more.
- Was that a correct figure?

1490
01:29:49,385 --> 01:29:51,928
No, it was closer to 1 million.

1491
01:29:53,055 --> 01:29:55,265
And as treasurer,
you could release those funds?

1492
01:29:55,766 --> 01:29:57,767
When so ordered.

1493
01:29:57,935 --> 01:29:59,978
BOB:
We don't know who could order you.

1494
01:30:00,145 --> 01:30:02,313
- We just know there were four.
- There were five.

1495
01:30:02,481 --> 01:30:05,316
- Five? - Mitchell, Stans, Magruder,
they're obvious.

1496
01:30:05,484 --> 01:30:07,777
Well, there had to be
a White House overseer.

1497
01:30:07,945 --> 01:30:09,612
- Yeah, Colson.
- What?

1498
01:30:09,780 --> 01:30:13,741
No, Colson's too smart to get involved
directly with anything like that.

1499
01:30:14,785 --> 01:30:16,369
It's Haldeman.

1500
01:30:18,789 --> 01:30:20,290
Right?

1501
01:30:21,333 --> 01:30:23,042
I won't talk about the other two.

1502
01:30:23,210 --> 01:30:25,545
BOB: They both worked at the White House?
- One did.

1503
01:30:25,713 --> 01:30:28,631
The other one's not in Washington,
but that's all I'll say.

1504
01:30:28,799 --> 01:30:30,425
- Kalmbach.
- Nixon's personal lawyer.

1505
01:30:30,593 --> 01:30:31,676
- Yeah.
- Right?

1506
01:30:31,844 --> 01:30:34,846
BOB: Nixon's personal lawyer?
- I can't say anything. I'm sorry.

1507
01:30:37,308 --> 01:30:39,309
- Well...
- When's the baby due?

1508
01:30:41,353 --> 01:30:44,230
Um, soon. Next month.

1509
01:30:44,398 --> 01:30:45,732
Are you gonna stay here?

1510
01:30:45,899 --> 01:30:49,027
- No, I don't think so.
- You decided where you're gonna go?

1511
01:30:49,194 --> 01:30:52,989
I've been looking for a job
in the private sector, but it's...

1512
01:30:53,157 --> 01:30:55,867
It's very hard.
My name's been in the papers too much.

1513
01:30:57,661 --> 01:31:01,039
- You know one thing I'm not clear about?
- What?

1514
01:31:01,206 --> 01:31:02,624
I don't know how... How did...?

1515
01:31:02,791 --> 01:31:05,710
When you handed out the money,
how did that work exactly?

1516
01:31:05,878 --> 01:31:07,795
Badly.

1517
01:31:10,424 --> 01:31:11,466
[CHUCKLES]

1518
01:31:11,634 --> 01:31:14,802
I think what Bob means is,
ordinarily, what was the procedure?

1519
01:31:15,220 --> 01:31:18,514
Routine. I'd call John Mitchell
over at the Justice Department.

1520
01:31:18,682 --> 01:31:22,268
- He'd say, "Go ahead, give out the money."
CARL: This was all done verbally?

1521
01:31:23,520 --> 01:31:24,896
Yes.

1522
01:31:25,314 --> 01:31:27,982
We know there were five men
who controlled the slush fund.

1523
01:31:28,150 --> 01:31:30,652
- Mitchell, Stans and Magruder.
- Those three we've got.

1524
01:31:30,819 --> 01:31:34,197
- All three have been named by two sources.
- What about the other two?

1525
01:31:34,365 --> 01:31:36,407
CARL: Kalmbach.
BOB: We're pretty sure of Kalmbach.

1526
01:31:36,575 --> 01:31:39,577
Maybe you'd better wait
till we get all five, huh?

1527
01:31:39,745 --> 01:31:40,787
Certain on Mitchell?

1528
01:31:40,954 --> 01:31:44,123
We know he approved payments to Liddy
while he was attorney general.

1529
01:31:44,291 --> 01:31:45,917
- You got more than one source?
CARL & BOB: Yes.

1530
01:31:46,085 --> 01:31:47,126
HOWARD: Who are they?
BOB: Sloan.

1531
01:31:47,294 --> 01:31:48,336
Sloan and who else?

1532
01:31:48,504 --> 01:31:52,173
Another guy at Justice who won't confirm
the other two who controlled the fund.

1533
01:31:52,341 --> 01:31:54,759
- What about Deep Throat?
BOB: He's not a source on this.

1534
01:31:54,927 --> 01:31:56,427
HOWARD: Do any of them have an ax?
- Nope.

1535
01:31:56,595 --> 01:31:59,347
Personal, political, sexual?
Anything at all on Mitchell?

1536
01:31:59,515 --> 01:32:00,807
- No.
- Can we use their names?

1537
01:32:00,974 --> 01:32:02,266
- No.
- Goddamn it.

1538
01:32:02,434 --> 01:32:04,977
When is somebody gonna go on the record
in this story?

1539
01:32:08,315 --> 01:32:11,609
You are about to write a story
that says the former attorney general...

1540
01:32:11,777 --> 01:32:15,655
...the highest-ranking law-enforcement
officer in this country, is a crook.

1541
01:32:18,617 --> 01:32:20,952
Just be sure you're right.

1542
01:32:22,329 --> 01:32:23,621
[LINE RINGING]

1543
01:32:23,789 --> 01:32:26,916
WOMAN: Essex House, may I help you?
- John Mitchell.

1544
01:32:27,084 --> 01:32:29,085
[LINE RINGING]

1545
01:32:34,800 --> 01:32:36,342
MITCHELL:
Yes?

1546
01:32:36,510 --> 01:32:38,970
Sir, this is Carl Bernstein
of the Washington Post...

1547
01:32:39,138 --> 01:32:41,597
...and I'm sorry to disturb you
at this hour.

1548
01:32:41,765 --> 01:32:45,184
Tomorrow we're running a story
in the paper...

1549
01:32:45,352 --> 01:32:49,605
...and we just think that you should
have a chance to comment on it.

1550
01:32:50,774 --> 01:32:52,483
What does it say?

1551
01:32:52,651 --> 01:32:58,114
"John N. Mitchell, while serving
as United States attorney general...

1552
01:32:58,282 --> 01:33:00,867
...personally controlled
a secret cash fund...

1553
01:33:01,034 --> 01:33:03,453
...used to gather information
about the Democrats...

1554
01:33:03,620 --> 01:33:06,998
...according to sources involved
in the Watergate investigation."

1555
01:33:07,166 --> 01:33:09,876
- Jesus.
- "Beginning in the spring of 1971...

1556
01:33:10,043 --> 01:33:12,336
...a year before
he left the Justice Department...

1557
01:33:12,504 --> 01:33:14,756
...to become President Nixon's
campaign manager.

1558
01:33:14,923 --> 01:33:19,135
On March 1, Mitchell personally approved
withdrawals from the fund."

1559
01:33:19,303 --> 01:33:21,721
All that crap,
you're putting it in the paper?

1560
01:33:21,889 --> 01:33:24,599
- Well...
- Look, it's all been denied.

1561
01:33:24,767 --> 01:33:26,684
Tell your publisher, tell Katie Graham...

1562
01:33:26,852 --> 01:33:30,062
...she's gonna get her tit caught
in a big ringer if that's published.

1563
01:33:30,230 --> 01:33:32,690
Christ, that's the most sickening thing
I ever heard.

1564
01:33:32,858 --> 01:33:35,943
- I wonder if I could ask you
some questions. - What time is it?

1565
01:33:36,111 --> 01:33:38,112
It's 11:30, sir.

1566
01:33:38,280 --> 01:33:40,239
Eleven-thirty?

1567
01:33:40,407 --> 01:33:43,576
- Is it morning or night?
- It's 11:30 at night, sir.

1568
01:33:43,744 --> 01:33:46,579
- Oh.
- Sir, the Committee to Reelect...

1569
01:33:46,747 --> 01:33:50,541
...has issued a statement to our story,
but there are a couple questions...

1570
01:33:50,709 --> 01:33:53,753
Did the committee tell you
to go ahead and publish the story?

1571
01:33:53,921 --> 01:33:56,506
You fellas have a great ball game going.

1572
01:33:56,673 --> 01:34:00,218
As soon as you're done,
we're gonna do a story on all of you.

1573
01:34:00,385 --> 01:34:02,721
Sir, there's just a couple of questions...

1574
01:34:02,722 --> 01:34:05,056
Call my law office in the morning.

1575
01:34:07,017 --> 01:34:09,560
There's no question
you properly identified yourself?

1576
01:34:09,728 --> 01:34:11,771
Said it right off the top.

1577
01:34:13,023 --> 01:34:15,108
Mitchell know he was
talking to a reporter?

1578
01:34:15,109 --> 01:34:17,193
Yeah, but I think
I woke him up.

1579
01:34:17,778 --> 01:34:20,696
- You have good notes?
- Verbatim.

1580
01:34:21,573 --> 01:34:24,575
He really said that about Mrs. Graham?

1581
01:34:25,869 --> 01:34:27,870
Well, cut the words "her tit" and print it.

1582
01:34:28,038 --> 01:34:30,748
- Why?
- This is a family newspaper.

1583
01:34:31,500 --> 01:34:33,501
[SIGHS]

1584
01:34:34,545 --> 01:34:35,837
Once when I was reporting...

1585
01:34:36,004 --> 01:34:38,923
...Lyndon Johnson's top guy
gave me the word...

1586
01:34:39,091 --> 01:34:42,176
...they were looking for a successor
for J. Edgar Hoover.

1587
01:34:42,344 --> 01:34:46,055
I wrote it, and the day it appeared,
Johnson held a press conference...

1588
01:34:46,223 --> 01:34:49,559
...and appointed Hoover
head of the FBI for life.

1589
01:34:49,726 --> 01:34:52,270
When he was done,
he turned to his top guy...

1590
01:34:52,437 --> 01:34:55,231
...and the president said, "Call Ben
Bradlee and tell him, 'Fuck you."'

1591
01:34:55,399 --> 01:34:56,649
[CHUCKLES]

1592
01:34:56,817 --> 01:34:59,318
Then everybody said,
"You did it, Ben. You screwed up.

1593
01:34:59,486 --> 01:35:02,530
You stuck us with Hoover forever."

1594
01:35:02,698 --> 01:35:04,323
I screwed up...

1595
01:35:04,491 --> 01:35:07,076
...but I wasn't wrong. Hm.

1596
01:35:09,288 --> 01:35:12,123
How much can you tell me
about Deep Throat?

1597
01:35:13,250 --> 01:35:15,251
How much do you need to know?

1598
01:35:15,419 --> 01:35:17,211
Do you trust him?

1599
01:35:18,839 --> 01:35:20,298
Yeah.

1600
01:35:22,134 --> 01:35:27,305
I can't do the reporting for my reporters,
which means I have to trust them.

1601
01:35:28,390 --> 01:35:31,183
And I hate trusting anybody.

1602
01:35:38,901 --> 01:35:40,985
Run that baby.

1603
01:36:20,150 --> 01:36:22,173
MAN [ON TV]: The Washington
Post reported that

1604
01:36:22,174 --> 01:36:24,195
while still in office
as attorney general...

1605
01:36:24,363 --> 01:36:28,532
...John Mitchell had personally controlled
a secret Republican fund.

1606
01:36:28,700 --> 01:36:32,662
Mitchell denied any such involvement
and called the story "ludicrous."

1607
01:36:32,829 --> 01:36:36,165
The new charge also brought a response
from Vice President Agnew...

1608
01:36:36,333 --> 01:36:37,708
...at his stop in Tampa.

1609
01:36:37,876 --> 01:36:41,295
I have full confidence in Mr. Mitchell...

1610
01:36:41,463 --> 01:36:44,423
...and in the people
in the Republican organization...

1611
01:36:44,591 --> 01:36:48,386
...and I think that
that kind of unattributed report...

1612
01:36:48,553 --> 01:36:51,555
...at a time like this
is counterproductive.

1613
01:36:51,723 --> 01:36:56,227
We must bear in mind
that those who published it...

1614
01:36:56,395 --> 01:36:59,063
...have already shown their sympathy
for the other ticket.

1615
01:36:59,690 --> 01:37:02,608
MAN: A band and some young cheerleaders...
- All non-denial denials.

1616
01:37:02,776 --> 01:37:05,987
They doubt our ancestry, but they
don't say the story isn't accurate.

1617
01:37:06,154 --> 01:37:08,114
Did you understand
one thing he was saying?

1618
01:37:08,281 --> 01:37:11,075
CARL: What I can't figure out is,
what is a real denial?

1619
01:37:11,243 --> 01:37:15,287
Well, if they start calling us goddamn
liars, we better start circling the wagons.

1620
01:37:15,455 --> 01:37:18,249
- When you think they'll start doing that?
- When they get out of Tampa.

1621
01:37:18,417 --> 01:37:19,583
[ALL LAUGH]

1622
01:37:20,252 --> 01:37:22,753
CARL: Joe, come on,
what's going on with you guys at the FBI?

1623
01:37:22,921 --> 01:37:26,090
I've been trying to get you for weeks.
Secretary says you're not in.

1624
01:37:26,258 --> 01:37:28,092
Last night, you said you couldn't talk.

1625
01:37:28,260 --> 01:37:30,928
This morning, soon as our
Mitchell story hits the stands...

1626
01:37:31,096 --> 01:37:33,556
...you call and say you gotta see me
right away. Why?

1627
01:37:33,724 --> 01:37:36,142
You guys have been causing big trouble
at the bureau.

1628
01:37:36,309 --> 01:37:37,518
Why?

1629
01:37:37,686 --> 01:37:41,063
Our reports are showing up
in your paper almost verbatim.

1630
01:37:41,231 --> 01:37:44,900
I mean, you've really been on the mark,
except for Mitchell.

1631
01:37:45,068 --> 01:37:47,278
Now, we didn't have that...

1632
01:37:47,446 --> 01:37:48,946
...that he controlled the funds.

1633
01:37:49,114 --> 01:37:50,448
Right.

1634
01:37:50,615 --> 01:37:52,241
Our agents have been busting ass...

1635
01:37:52,409 --> 01:37:55,036
...but we're gonna go back
and see if we missed anything.

1636
01:37:55,203 --> 01:37:58,706
What I don't understand is all the people
who know details of the bugging...

1637
01:37:58,874 --> 01:38:00,416
...the FBI hasn't even talked to.

1638
01:38:00,584 --> 01:38:04,128
Why have you conducted interviews of
CREEP personnel at CREEP headquarters...

1639
01:38:04,296 --> 01:38:07,381
...instead of at their homes,
where they might feel freer to talk?

1640
01:38:07,549 --> 01:38:08,632
Joe, wait a minute.

1641
01:38:08,800 --> 01:38:11,469
Why have the interviews at CREEP
always been conducted...

1642
01:38:11,636 --> 01:38:14,305
...within the presence of the lawyer
who works for CREEP?

1643
01:38:14,473 --> 01:38:17,141
Look, you know,
I can't answer for the whole bureau.

1644
01:38:17,309 --> 01:38:20,478
- Oh, come on, I'm just...
- I do what I'm told.

1645
01:38:21,646 --> 01:38:24,065
I followed my orders, period.

1646
01:38:30,030 --> 01:38:31,822
What orders?

1647
01:38:35,285 --> 01:38:38,662
CARL:
Woodward! Woodward!

1648
01:38:40,165 --> 01:38:41,624
Wait!

1649
01:38:42,584 --> 01:38:44,043
Bob!

1650
01:38:46,588 --> 01:38:49,715
Out of the blue. Out of the blue.

1651
01:38:51,093 --> 01:38:54,303
This morning I get a tip to call a
guy by the name of Alex Shipley...

1652
01:38:54,471 --> 01:38:57,139
...who is now the assistant
attorney general of Tennessee.

1653
01:38:57,307 --> 01:38:59,558
Now, the guy told me that called me...
That said...

1654
01:38:59,726 --> 01:39:02,269
He said that Shipley was asked
in the summer of 1971...

1655
01:39:02,437 --> 01:39:04,814
...by an old Army buddy,
a Donald Segretti...

1656
01:39:04,981 --> 01:39:06,774
...to join a group of other lawyers...

1657
01:39:06,942 --> 01:39:09,819
...for Nixon's campaign
to sabotage the Democratic candidates.

1658
01:39:09,986 --> 01:39:13,114
- Make a left. We'll go to my place.
- Sabotage Democratic candidates?

1659
01:39:13,281 --> 01:39:15,220
CARL: I was able to make
a couple calls, and

1660
01:39:15,221 --> 01:39:17,159
I got Segretti's records
for the year...

1661
01:39:17,327 --> 01:39:20,746
His travel records for the year 1971-'72.

1662
01:39:20,914 --> 01:39:21,956
Does the FBI know...?

1663
01:39:22,124 --> 01:39:24,125
- Did you say left or right?
- Left, my place.

1664
01:39:24,292 --> 01:39:27,419
- We gotta go through the records.
- Does the FBI know about Segretti?

1665
01:39:27,587 --> 01:39:30,714
FBI interrogated Segretti,
found he wasn't involved in the break-in.

1666
01:39:30,882 --> 01:39:32,716
They dropped it, didn't follow through.

1667
01:39:32,884 --> 01:39:34,426
BOB: Where is he?
CARL: He's in California.

1668
01:39:35,053 --> 01:39:36,554
BOB: Jesus, look at this.
CARL: What?

1669
01:39:36,721 --> 01:39:39,390
BOB: Segretti crisscrossed the country
at least a dozen times.

1670
01:39:42,227 --> 01:39:45,020
Only stayed in cities
where there were Democratic primaries.

1671
01:39:45,188 --> 01:39:47,064
CARL:
If the break-in was just one incident...

1672
01:39:47,232 --> 01:39:49,859
...in a campaign of sabotage
that began a year before...

1673
01:39:50,026 --> 01:39:52,069
BOB: For the first time,
the break-in makes sense.

1674
01:39:52,237 --> 01:39:53,279
CARL:
This isn't so crazy.

1675
01:39:53,446 --> 01:39:55,573
This whole thing didn't start
with the bugging.

1676
01:39:55,740 --> 01:39:58,033
Segretti was doing this
a year before the bugging.

1677
01:39:58,201 --> 01:40:00,744
And a year before,
Nixon was running behind Muskie...

1678
01:40:00,912 --> 01:40:03,205
...before Muskie self-destructed.

1679
01:40:03,999 --> 01:40:05,916
If he self-destructed.

1680
01:40:06,793 --> 01:40:09,461
CARL: Hi. Uh, Donald Segretti?
- That's right.

1681
01:40:09,629 --> 01:40:12,923
I'm Carl Bernstein
from the Washington Post.

1682
01:40:13,091 --> 01:40:14,675
Hi.

1683
01:40:15,427 --> 01:40:16,677
What can I do for you?

1684
01:40:16,845 --> 01:40:21,599
Well, my paper just sent me out here
to try to persuade you to go on the record.

1685
01:40:21,766 --> 01:40:22,766
Why me?

1686
01:40:22,934 --> 01:40:24,810
Because you were the head coordinator...

1687
01:40:24,978 --> 01:40:28,856
...of Nixon's sabotage campaign
against the Democrats.

1688
01:40:29,691 --> 01:40:33,277
- Carl, you want some coffee?
- You read my mind.

1689
01:40:38,617 --> 01:40:41,619
Carl, tell me something. What...?

1690
01:40:41,786 --> 01:40:44,121
What do you imagine
the head coordinator does?

1691
01:40:44,289 --> 01:40:48,083
I guess basically you were involved
in recruiting other people like yourself...

1692
01:40:48,251 --> 01:40:49,293
...other lawyers.

1693
01:40:49,461 --> 01:40:52,838
- Lawyers?
- Like Alex Shipley.

1694
01:40:53,006 --> 01:40:57,259
I made it clear that I would not
do anything violent or illegal.

1695
01:40:57,802 --> 01:40:59,803
What do you mean by illegal?

1696
01:40:59,971 --> 01:41:03,432
Watergate. I mean, that's...
The whole bugging, that's horrendous.

1697
01:41:04,059 --> 01:41:06,310
And what kind of stuff
do you guys do, then?

1698
01:41:06,478 --> 01:41:08,687
Nickel-and-dime stuff.

1699
01:41:09,439 --> 01:41:10,648
Stuff.

1700
01:41:10,815 --> 01:41:12,733
Stuff with a little wit attached to it.

1701
01:41:12,901 --> 01:41:15,319
You mean when you sent out
on Muskie's stationery...

1702
01:41:15,487 --> 01:41:18,489
...that Senator Hubert Humphrey
was going out with call girls?

1703
01:41:18,949 --> 01:41:21,784
Listen, if anything,
it helped the man's image.

1704
01:41:21,952 --> 01:41:24,495
What was the one
on Muskie's stationery you sent out...

1705
01:41:24,955 --> 01:41:28,707
...that said that Scoop Jackson
was having a bastard child?

1706
01:41:28,875 --> 01:41:31,835
So sometimes it got up to a quarter,
off the record.

1707
01:41:32,837 --> 01:41:36,966
I think one of the most interesting ones
was the "Canuck" letter.

1708
01:41:37,842 --> 01:41:38,842
What about it?

1709
01:41:40,011 --> 01:41:43,347
Come on. Where you claimed
that Muskie slurred the Canadians.

1710
01:41:43,515 --> 01:41:45,849
No, I didn't write that.

1711
01:41:46,017 --> 01:41:47,017
Do you know who did?

1712
01:41:47,185 --> 01:41:50,312
Carl, when you guys print it in the papers,
then I'll know.

1713
01:41:50,480 --> 01:41:52,982
Smart guy, Donald.

1714
01:41:53,149 --> 01:41:54,191
You're no dummy.

1715
01:41:55,610 --> 01:41:57,695
I'm a lawyer, Carl.

1716
01:41:57,862 --> 01:41:59,154
I'm a lawyer.

1717
01:41:59,322 --> 01:42:00,864
I'm a good lawyer...

1718
01:42:01,032 --> 01:42:04,702
...and I'll probably wind up going to jail
and being disbarred.

1719
01:42:06,913 --> 01:42:10,666
And I don't know what I did
that was so goddamn awful.

1720
01:42:15,547 --> 01:42:18,507
I'll tell you something.
None of this was my idea.

1721
01:42:18,675 --> 01:42:22,636
- I didn't go looking for the job.
- Well, that's important.

1722
01:42:23,638 --> 01:42:25,681
Chapin came to you.

1723
01:42:32,105 --> 01:42:33,147
You know what?

1724
01:42:33,315 --> 01:42:37,401
It's funny, but I keep forgetting
that you guys knew each other in college.

1725
01:42:37,569 --> 01:42:41,488
You were friends at SC, you and Chapin.
Who else was there?

1726
01:42:41,906 --> 01:42:43,741
There was me...

1727
01:42:43,908 --> 01:42:45,534
...Dwight...

1728
01:42:45,702 --> 01:42:46,952
...Ziegler.

1729
01:42:47,120 --> 01:42:48,579
The whole USC mafia.

1730
01:42:48,747 --> 01:42:51,540
And that's when you got involved
in the student elections...

1731
01:42:51,708 --> 01:42:55,753
...and started to try to get your man in,
so you stuffed ballot boxes and...

1732
01:42:55,920 --> 01:42:58,881
What was that term you guys used
for screwing up the opposition?

1733
01:42:59,591 --> 01:43:02,301
- Rat-fucking.
- That's right.

1734
01:43:02,469 --> 01:43:03,927
You were doing the same stuff...

1735
01:43:04,095 --> 01:43:06,764
...when you were out campaigning
for President Nixon.

1736
01:43:06,931 --> 01:43:09,850
Let me tell you something,
we did a lot of worse things in college.

1737
01:43:10,018 --> 01:43:11,101
[CHUCKLES]

1738
01:43:11,644 --> 01:43:14,396
Look, let me ask you something, Carl.

1739
01:43:14,564 --> 01:43:17,316
What would you have done
if you were just out of the Army...

1740
01:43:17,484 --> 01:43:19,151
...been away for four years...

1741
01:43:19,319 --> 01:43:22,613
...didn't know what kind of law
you wanted to practice...

1742
01:43:22,781 --> 01:43:25,282
...and one day you get a call
from an old friend...

1743
01:43:25,450 --> 01:43:28,994
...asking if you wanna go to work
for the president of the United States?

1744
01:43:29,162 --> 01:43:33,582
Jeez. Chapin was the appointment secretary
for Nixon when he called.

1745
01:43:33,750 --> 01:43:34,792
Yeah.

1746
01:43:34,959 --> 01:43:38,629
If those sinister things really happened,
I don't think Dwight knew about them.

1747
01:43:38,797 --> 01:43:42,299
- He just did what he was told.
- Told by who?

1748
01:43:53,144 --> 01:43:55,145
DEEP THROAT:
What's the topic for tonight?

1749
01:44:00,652 --> 01:44:02,152
Rat-fucking.

1750
01:44:04,114 --> 01:44:07,908
In my day, it was simply known
as a double-cross.

1751
01:44:08,076 --> 01:44:10,953
In our present context...

1752
01:44:11,913 --> 01:44:15,582
...it means infiltration of the Democrats.

1753
01:44:16,626 --> 01:44:19,044
Segretti won't go on the record...

1754
01:44:19,212 --> 01:44:21,713
...but if he would,
we know he would implicate Chapin.

1755
01:44:24,050 --> 01:44:26,677
And that would put you
inside the White House.

1756
01:44:28,012 --> 01:44:29,430
Who?

1757
01:44:31,307 --> 01:44:33,308
Can you be specific?

1758
01:44:33,852 --> 01:44:35,352
How high up?

1759
01:44:38,523 --> 01:44:41,567
You'll have to find that out for yourself.

1760
01:44:42,777 --> 01:44:45,612
I don't like newspapers.

1761
01:44:46,823 --> 01:44:52,035
I don't care for inexactitude
and shallowness.

1762
01:44:53,705 --> 01:44:55,456
The CREEP slush fund...

1763
01:44:55,623 --> 01:44:59,001
...that financed the rat-fucking,
we've just about got that nailed down.

1764
01:44:59,169 --> 01:45:00,544
Did you change cabs?

1765
01:45:08,303 --> 01:45:09,803
BOB:
Yeah.

1766
01:45:09,971 --> 01:45:13,098
Does the FBI know what we know?

1767
01:45:16,394 --> 01:45:18,395
Does Justice?

1768
01:45:22,233 --> 01:45:24,735
Why haven't they done anything?

1769
01:45:25,320 --> 01:45:30,240
If it didn't deal directly with
the break-in, they didn't pursue.

1770
01:45:30,783 --> 01:45:32,451
Who told them not to?

1771
01:45:32,911 --> 01:45:35,913
Don't you understand what you're on to?

1772
01:45:39,250 --> 01:45:42,127
- Mitchell knew?
- Of course Mitchell knew.

1773
01:45:43,129 --> 01:45:45,881
Do you think something this size
just happens?

1774
01:45:46,049 --> 01:45:47,925
Haldeman had to know too.

1775
01:45:48,092 --> 01:45:51,220
You'll get nothing from me
about Haldeman.

1776
01:45:54,891 --> 01:45:56,225
Segretti said that...

1777
01:45:56,392 --> 01:46:00,729
Don't concentrate on Segretti.
You'll miss the overall.

1778
01:46:01,981 --> 01:46:05,526
The letter that destroyed
the Muskie candidacy...

1779
01:46:05,693 --> 01:46:07,778
...did that come
from inside the White House?

1780
01:46:07,946 --> 01:46:11,031
- You're missing the overall.
- But what overall?

1781
01:46:11,199 --> 01:46:14,284
They were frightened of Muskie,
and look who got destroyed.

1782
01:46:14,744 --> 01:46:18,455
They wanted to run against McGovern.
Look who they're running against.

1783
01:46:18,623 --> 01:46:21,875
They bugged, they followed people.

1784
01:46:22,043 --> 01:46:24,711
False press leaks, fake letters.

1785
01:46:25,255 --> 01:46:27,464
They canceled
Democratic campaign rallies.

1786
01:46:27,632 --> 01:46:30,592
They investigated
Democratic private lives.

1787
01:46:31,511 --> 01:46:34,179
They planted spies, stole documents,
and on and on.

1788
01:46:34,347 --> 01:46:37,099
Now, don't tell me
you think this is all the work...

1789
01:46:37,267 --> 01:46:39,810
...of little Don Segretti.

1790
01:46:41,229 --> 01:46:43,313
The FBI and Justice know this?

1791
01:46:47,151 --> 01:46:48,860
[CAR ENGINE STARTS]

1792
01:46:50,697 --> 01:46:52,698
[TIRES SCREECH]

1793
01:49:00,243 --> 01:49:02,244
[CHATTERING]

1794
01:49:07,208 --> 01:49:10,669
MAN 1: Send me the clips
on the Food and Drug story.

1795
01:49:12,130 --> 01:49:14,506
MAN 2:
Yes, sir, and I want... My question is...

1796
01:49:14,674 --> 01:49:15,716
- Carl.
- Yeah?

1797
01:49:15,883 --> 01:49:17,592
Why don't you pick up your messages?

1798
01:49:17,760 --> 01:49:19,720
- Right. You got a cigarette?
- Yeah.

1799
01:49:19,887 --> 01:49:20,929
Who's Pete Teller?

1800
01:49:21,097 --> 01:49:24,266
Haven't the slightest idea.
I have this whole place to take care of.

1801
01:49:24,434 --> 01:49:26,977
- Carl?
- Yeah, one second.

1802
01:49:28,146 --> 01:49:30,439
- Tell him to leave his number next time.
- Will do.

1803
01:49:30,606 --> 01:49:32,733
- Hi.
- You guys know about the "Canuck" letter?

1804
01:49:32,900 --> 01:49:34,067
Yep. I'm sorry, I'm late.

1805
01:49:34,235 --> 01:49:37,112
I just wanna make sure
you know who wrote it, though.

1806
01:49:38,156 --> 01:49:39,573
CARL:
What?

1807
01:49:39,907 --> 01:49:40,991
What?

1808
01:49:41,159 --> 01:49:44,786
You mean the letter that sabotaged
the Muskie candidacy? All right, come here.

1809
01:49:44,954 --> 01:49:47,914
- When did he tell you this?
- I already told you...

1810
01:49:49,959 --> 01:49:51,710
I gotta tell Bob.

1811
01:49:55,381 --> 01:49:57,466
- Woodward.
BOB: What?

1812
01:49:57,925 --> 01:50:00,802
CARL: One second.
Come here, come here, come here.

1813
01:50:01,262 --> 01:50:04,514
Come here. Tell him what you told me.

1814
01:50:04,932 --> 01:50:06,725
Come here, sit down.

1815
01:50:08,269 --> 01:50:11,480
Just exactly the way you said it to me,
just say it to him.

1816
01:50:12,356 --> 01:50:14,608
Ken Clawson told me
he wrote the "Canuck" letter.

1817
01:50:14,776 --> 01:50:17,319
CARL: The letter that said Muskie
was slurring the Canadians.

1818
01:50:17,487 --> 01:50:20,697
The deputy director of Communications
wrote the "Canuck" letter.

1819
01:50:20,865 --> 01:50:22,949
- When did he tell you?
- We were having drinks.

1820
01:50:23,117 --> 01:50:24,701
CARL: Where were you?
- My apartment.

1821
01:50:25,161 --> 01:50:26,495
CARL:
When did you say he told you?

1822
01:50:26,662 --> 01:50:28,538
SALLY: Two weeks ago.
CARL: What else did he say?

1823
01:50:28,706 --> 01:50:30,874
He didn't say anything?
Come on, you're hedging.

1824
01:50:31,042 --> 01:50:33,710
Do you think he said it
to get you to go to bed with him?

1825
01:50:33,878 --> 01:50:35,587
CARL: Jesus.
